{"term":"1957","caseName":"County of Marin v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/415","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 09, 1958 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13406","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":0,"stop":6.234,"duration":6.23},{"text":"(Inaudible) of civil rules does apply in appropriate circumstances to the amendment of a complaint seeking review of an administrative order.","start":6.234,"stop":17.258,"duration":11.02},{"text":"We submit that there was no abuse of discretion on the part of the three-judge court in this case in denying the appellant's motion to amend because again, this was not a routine motion to amend filed at an early stage in the proceedings, rather it came so late that it amounted to a deliberate attempt to split up to what would normally be a single review proceeding, a single day in court into a piecemeal review of an administrative order because the appellant stated candidly to the three-judge court that they would seek to amend their complaint.","start":17.258,"stop":62.171,"duration":44.91},{"text":"If the one question under Section 5, which they had raised in their original complaint, if that question was resolved against them, then they would like to amend to -- to litigate some further questions.","start":62.171,"stop":76.072,"duration":13.9},{"text":"And raising -- raising the question on amendment that late is essentially the same, we submit, in terms of the wasting of judicial time and the harassment of parties, as if they had actually waited until the three-judge court had rendered its decision and judgment upon the one point raised in the complaint.","start":76.072,"stop":98.027,"duration":21.96},{"text":"Now, such repetitive review, such piecemeal review of Commission orders, we submit, is repugnant to the whole pattern of arrangements which Congress has provided and indeed which this Court has impart provided for the review of administrative orders.","start":98.027,"stop":115.815,"duration":17.79},{"text":"Some years ago in the United States v. Griffin, this Court had occasioned to analyze the review provisions provided for the review of Interstate Commerce Commission orders.","start":115.815,"stop":126.943,"duration":11.13},{"text":"And the Court specifically adverted to the fact that Congress sought to avert the delays incident to litigation.","start":126.943,"stop":135.907,"duration":8.96},{"text":"And in many recent regulatory statutes, almost typically, Congress has specified a period within which proceedings for judicial review of particular types of administrative orders must be brought, such periods are typically 30 or 60 days.","start":135.907,"stop":153.471,"duration":17.56},{"text":"But this whole pattern of congressional purpose and the purpose of this Court were reasonably expeditious review of orders for a single day in the Court for those that want to challenge regulatory orders is thwarted.","start":153.471,"stop":167.314,"duration":13.84},{"text":"If this new theory of a piecemeal ruling review of orders and the guides of amendments to complaints is accepted, if this -- in many respects, we view this aspect of the case as more important than the subsequent law aspect because in these rate cases in particular, and I emphasize I -- this is no reflection on the parties to this case, I'm just speaking generally, in these rate cases, delay is typically worth a great deal to one side or the other.","start":167.314,"stop":202.287,"duration":34.97},{"text":"Delay is precious to the carrier if it has rate -- if it has rates in effect.","start":202.287,"stop":208.333,"duration":6.05},{"text":"Delay is precious to the protesters if the carrier can't get rate -- can't get rates into effect.","start":208.333,"stop":215.415,"duration":7.08},{"text":"And if, by a theory of amendments to complaints, orders of the Interstate Commerce Commission and other orders of federal regulatory agencies can be subjected to this kind of piecemeal review, then they'll -- then it -- that there will have been created a unique procedure for dilatory tactics.","start":215.415,"stop":235.433,"duration":20.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you say this would have delayed the carrier?","start":235.433,"stop":238.824,"duration":3.39},{"text":"I can understand your argument that you will not be allowed (Inaudible)","start":238.824,"stop":247.421,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I review the posture of the case?","start":247.421,"stop":249.573,"duration":2.15},{"text":"A complaint filed --","start":249.573,"stop":250.892,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":250.892,"stop":251.164,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- responsive pleadings, briefs, briefs on the merits of the one question under Section 5, which the appellant raised in their original complaint, counsel for the parties, assemblance San Francisco before the three-judge court, argument is held on the merits of the one question raised in the original complaint.","start":251.164,"stop":270.356,"duration":19.19},{"text":"And in the course of that argument for the first time, the Court has told, the defendants are told by the appellants that if this one question raised by them in their complaint is resolved against them by the three-judge court, then they'd like to amend their complaint to litigate some further questions.","start":270.356,"stop":289.236,"duration":18.88},{"text":"And we submit that that sort of --","start":289.236,"stop":291.466,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) delay in this particular case?","start":291.466,"stop":299.47,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It would have been --","start":299.47,"stop":299.819,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What delay would have been brought about?","start":299.819,"stop":301.731,"duration":1.91},{"text":"When was the case -- when did they ask him and when did the case decided?","start":301.731,"stop":307.42,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the case was argued in -- on February 23.","start":307.42,"stop":310.814,"duration":3.39},{"text":"On February 28, they filed this motion for leave to amend.","start":310.814,"stop":313.743,"duration":2.93},{"text":"Now, in this -- in this particular case --","start":313.743,"stop":314.848,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Beginning what year?","start":314.848,"stop":316.213,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"1956.","start":316.213,"stop":316.96,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"When was it decided?","start":316.96,"stop":318.705,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Three-judge court handed down its decision in April of 1957.","start":318.705,"stop":323.178,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"14 months.","start":323.178,"stop":323.98,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"14 months.","start":323.98,"stop":325.336,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why would it delay the judge to let them do that if they claim that they had just placed for the witness to testify the one thing they had discovered that he testified quite another (Inaudible)","start":325.336,"stop":339.676,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I say this without intending the slightness reflection or criticism of the three-judge court.","start":339.676,"stop":345.035,"duration":5.36},{"text":"At the time this idea of amending the complaint was raised, their argument before the Court in February of 1956, none of the parties had any idea when the three-judge court would come down to its decision.","start":345.035,"stop":360.091,"duration":15.06},{"text":"For all we knew, they -- they might have handed down a decision four or five weeks later.","start":360.091,"stop":364.358,"duration":4.27},{"text":"In --","start":364.358,"stop":364.607,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"We know now when it --","start":364.607,"stop":365.454,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We know now.","start":365.454,"stop":367.332,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It was 14 months.","start":367.332,"stop":369.48,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"What I -- what I do --","start":369.48,"stop":370.124,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your judgment that -- that they could have decided it necessarily later beyond that 14 months to let them (Inaudible) again?","start":370.124,"stop":378.073,"duration":7.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course not, sir.","start":378.073,"stop":379.514,"duration":1.44},{"text":"But -- but I am saying that in the -- that in the ordinary three-judge case, nothing like 14 months elapses between argument and decision.","start":379.514,"stop":388.578,"duration":9.06},{"text":"And that -- and that in the average case to permit this sort of rewriting of the complaint at or following a hearing on the merits, perhaps once, perhaps twice for the limit that that -- that will delay the completion of these proceedings, it will -- it will prevent giving to these orders of administrative agencies the finality within a reasonable time, which Congress clearly has indicated that they should have.","start":388.578,"stop":418.421,"duration":29.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) general in flexible rule taking this out, idea that (Inaudible) as a matter of fact, it came to a court of justice, two judges and that people should be allowed to amend at anytime if they have some relevant reasons that will not do an injury to that case.","start":418.421,"stop":440.343,"duration":21.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I submit, sir, that Congress and this Court have defined justice in the review of administrative orders as containing some other -- some other factors too.","start":440.343,"stop":449.916,"duration":9.57},{"text":"Everybody should have their day in court, determines an I.C.C. order.","start":449.916,"stop":453.914,"duration":4},{"text":"What I'm suggesting is that this amendment business should be so restricted that people have one full day in court, not two or three.","start":453.914,"stop":460.701,"duration":6.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though -- even though it works a gross injustice in a particular case would not delay it at all, but you are saying, we shouldn't apply it, the general civil rule which was entered to achieve the ends of justice rather than the question.","start":460.701,"stop":474.387,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor refers to a gross injustice, but this was the appellant's choice, some tactical choice of theirs.","start":474.387,"stop":480.678,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know about the technical choice.","start":480.678,"stop":482.114,"duration":1.44},{"text":"All I know is that we've had a rule which we could use to consider very liberally.","start":482.114,"stop":484.099,"duration":1.99},{"text":"The rule says it can -- complains can be amended in a regular lawsuit even after the -- after the case has been argued and the charge has been made.","start":484.099,"stop":498.854,"duration":14.75},{"text":"That's the general idea of justice referred and you say that we should depart from it in connection with the challenges against the (Inaudible)","start":498.854,"stop":507.587,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the circumstance of this case, I certainly do, sir.","start":507.587,"stop":510.44,"duration":2.85},{"text":"And -- and whether it's the orders of the Interstate Commerce Commission or those of any federal agency.","start":510.44,"stop":515.346,"duration":4.91},{"text":"Congress has intended and this -- and this Court has recognized that intention and applied it, that -- that this regulatory orders many of which involved matters of great moment, the whole regions of the country.","start":515.346,"stop":528.817,"duration":13.47},{"text":"It shall -- it shall be final.","start":528.817,"stop":531.206,"duration":2.39},{"text":"It shall come to rest within a reasonable period of time, but then the reasonable period of time, which allows those who want to challenge it one day in court, not two days or three days.","start":531.206,"stop":542.932,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the --","start":542.932,"stop":543.292,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"And your -- and this Court has never departed from that principle, happily or haven't been asked to before.","start":543.292,"stop":548.223,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That one day -- that one day is the revenue concept, I think.","start":548.223,"stop":551.671,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's almost --","start":551.671,"stop":552.249,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that -- if you mean by that that while a case is in progress [Laughs], it goes on for two years.","start":552.249,"stop":560.41,"duration":8.16},{"text":"You got to stick to the original pleadings as the word.","start":560.41,"stop":562.949,"duration":2.54},{"text":"You will never go back on it because in some other case, it might delay a -- it might delay judgment.","start":562.949,"stop":568.939,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the District Court here deny this as a pure matter of discretion or did they go on even if they had no power to rule the amendment?","start":568.939,"stop":578.132,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Amending rule didn't have any application to I.C.C. (Voice Overlap) --","start":578.132,"stop":581.445,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of discretion.","start":581.445,"stop":584.61,"duration":3.16},{"text":"They did not take the position --","start":584.61,"stop":585.762,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We got any basis in this record for reaching a judgment as to whether the amendment or whether there was an -- whether a substantial attack could have been made on the findings of the Commission.","start":585.762,"stop":599.311,"duration":13.55},{"text":"We have no -- no way of judging that, have we?","start":599.311,"stop":602.559,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the record is not before you.","start":602.559,"stop":604.44,"duration":1.88},{"text":"For example, one of the issues they wanted to raise was that -- was that the Commission's findings were not supported by substantial evidence.","start":604.44,"stop":610.083,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I understood.","start":610.083,"stop":611.012,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that evidence is not before you.","start":611.012,"stop":613.579,"duration":2.57},{"text":"The plaintiffs did not choose to file the evidentiary record with the District Court and therefore, it was --","start":613.579,"stop":618.117,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And the District Court --","start":618.117,"stop":618.802,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- not certified to the Court.","start":618.802,"stop":619.491,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the District Court didn't have that before it either?","start":619.491,"stop":622.134,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":622.134,"stop":623.71,"duration":1.58},{"text":"The District Court had before it only the pleadings before the Commission and the Commission's report and the rest of this were in the record consist of the various court pleadings.","start":623.71,"stop":635.589,"duration":11.88},{"text":"None of the evidence is here.","start":635.589,"stop":636.859,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What language did the Court use in declining to permit the amendment?","start":636.859,"stop":641.279,"duration":4.42},{"text":"Did it use anything like the language of the rule or anything that was its equivalent?","start":641.279,"stop":653.447,"duration":12.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It's on page 118 of the record and the gist -- the gist of the court ruling appears to be as follows.","start":653.447,"stop":661.438,"duration":7.99},{"text":"It is sufficient to say that the power of the Court to permit amendment should not be used to completely change the theory of the case after the case has been submitted to the Court on another theory without some showing of lack of knowledge, mistake or inadvertence on the part of the parties seeking amendment or some change of conditions of which the party had no knowledge or control.","start":661.438,"stop":682.832,"duration":21.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that, as I recall it, is the language that was used in connection of those things many years.","start":682.832,"stop":690.194,"duration":7.36},{"text":"But state and the federal court before the (Inaudible) rules of amendment were adopted and that, as I recall it, is the language that's used frequently in reference to setting aside judgment by the power.","start":690.194,"stop":702.082,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":702.082,"stop":704.126,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So that he did (Inaudible) as far as his language is concerned.","start":704.126,"stop":707.394,"duration":3.27},{"text":"He used the language, which indicated his adherence to the idea that you had to satisfy the criteria for a judgment -- judgment by the Court set aside rather than make an amendment.","start":707.394,"stop":719.089,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"But in -- but in fairness to the three-judge court, I assume they were saying that in the context of the -- of the chronology of facts in this case.","start":719.089,"stop":726.777,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you argue there or did the Commission argued there that that the rule shouldn't apply?","start":726.777,"stop":731.052,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Rule 15?","start":731.052,"stop":733.151,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we -- we argued essentially on the facts.","start":733.151,"stop":737.807,"duration":4.66},{"text":"As I recall, we assumed that it applied to permit amendments under appropriate circumstances.","start":737.807,"stop":747.078,"duration":9.27},{"text":"I think we are -- I think our -- our whole argument was under the circumstances of this case, under the chronology of -- on this case.","start":747.078,"stop":753.468,"duration":6.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I --","start":753.468,"stop":753.87,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That then --","start":753.87,"stop":753.906,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- understand that argument.","start":753.906,"stop":754.886,"duration":0.98},{"text":"I think that's clear and valid agreement if -- if the fact is supported.","start":754.886,"stop":759.72,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"If the fact is supported, we think they do.","start":759.72,"stop":762.534,"duration":2.81},{"text":"As I say, this has been tried so seldom if at all that we do -- that we don't have much by way of precedent to point to.","start":762.534,"stop":770.878,"duration":8.34},{"text":"But Your Honors did have a somewhat similar question back in 281 U.S. in Grubb v. Public Utilities Commission of Ohio.","start":770.878,"stop":779.182,"duration":8.3},{"text":"And you dealt with it in language which we think fits here like a hat.","start":779.182,"stop":782.463,"duration":3.28},{"text":"And you said, “He was not at liberty to prosecute that right by piecemeal as by presenting a part only of the available grounds and reserving others for another suit if failing in that.”","start":782.463,"stop":799.92,"duration":17.46},{"text":"Now, that case involved --","start":799.92,"stop":800.195,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that we're saying is this, he isn't asking to have another suit.","start":800.195,"stop":805.323,"duration":5.13},{"text":"He merely asked to -- to amend his pleadings here so he can have it all determined in one suit.","start":805.323,"stop":813.705,"duration":8.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We think, as a practical matter, it's the same thing.","start":813.705,"stop":817.694,"duration":3.99},{"text":"He waited until he saw how his arguments on the first point, how they went with the three-judge court, then he said, \"Let's -- if we lose on that, we want to amend our complaint.\"","start":817.694,"stop":829.944,"duration":12.25},{"text":"That just isn't the way orders have been reviewed, administrative orders for the last 75 years under the rules laid down by Congress and this Court.","start":829.944,"stop":843.109,"duration":13.17},{"text":"I would like to turn now to the issue decided by the -- considered and decided by the court below as to whether this type of transaction is subject to the Commission's jurisdiction under Section 5 of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":843.109,"stop":863.814,"duration":20.7},{"text":"Now, the provision, which we think is pertinent and controlling, is that portion of Section 5 (a) (2) which provides that, “It shall be lawful, with the approval of the Commission, for any carrier to acquire control of another through ownership of its stock or by otherwise.”","start":863.814,"stop":883.123,"duration":19.31},{"text":"Now, here, the Commission exercised jurisdiction over a double transaction but to be consummated simultaneously, transaction by which Golden Gate would acquire certain carrier franchises and properties from Pacific Greyhound, thus making Golden -- Golden Gate a carrier, and at the same time, Pacific would still remain the carrier by reason of -- of the franchises and operations which would continue to operate.","start":883.123,"stop":913.377,"duration":30.25},{"text":"Pacific would acquire control of Golden Gate by taking all of its capital stock.","start":913.377,"stop":919.21,"duration":5.83},{"text":"In brief, what the Commission did was to determine what was happening, what had happened at the point when the transaction was consummated.","start":919.21,"stop":928.538,"duration":9.33},{"text":"Now, the appellant's argument briefly is that Section 5 (2) doesn't apply to what they refer to as split-ups of carriers as distinguished from consolidations or unifications.","start":928.538,"stop":940.943,"duration":12.4},{"text":"And as a parallel argument, they -- they contend that Section 5 doesn't apply unless using the names of this case, unless Golden Gate was a carrier prior to the beginning of these transactions.","start":940.943,"stop":958.299,"duration":17.36},{"text":"And they contend that the legislative history shows that Congress was not -- was not concerned to reach with Section 5, split-ups of carrier operation as distinguished from carrier unifications or consolidations.","start":958.299,"stop":973.874,"duration":15.58},{"text":"Well, now, to begin with, we think that as a matter of literal statutory language, just looking only at the language in a very literal way, this transaction was subject to Section 5 because by the -- by the time the transaction is completed, one carrier has acquired control of another.","start":973.874,"stop":994.241,"duration":20.37},{"text":"But more importantly, I think from the beginning, this Court has not interpreted Section 5 strictly or in any dictionary sense.","start":994.241,"stop":1005.083,"duration":10.84},{"text":"Were you going to ask me a question, sir?","start":1005.083,"stop":1007.156,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I was just going to -- to ask if the language didn't import the fact that -- that the Commission could give approval to a carrier not to make a carrier and then give it approval but to -- to give it to a carrier and if you can be a little more specific, I'd like to -- I like to know how you -- you -- why you claim that this company that never had anything to do with transportation before can be a carrier until the judgment becomes final.","start":1007.156,"stop":1051.401,"duration":44.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It can't become a carrier as you suggested.","start":1051.401,"stop":1053.497,"duration":2.1},{"text":"It can't become a carrier except upon the consummation of the transaction.","start":1053.497,"stop":1058.39,"duration":4.89},{"text":"For example, at the -- at the present time, Golden Gate is an empty corporate shell.Pending this litigation, the transaction has not been consummated.","start":1058.39,"stop":1067.755,"duration":9.37},{"text":"But if -- but when the transactions are authorized, if they are authorized, consummated is authorized by the Commission's order.","start":1067.755,"stop":1076.032,"duration":8.28},{"text":"And as they are completed, Golden Gate will be in the carrier business, admittedly carrying on carrier operations and it will be controlled by another carrier, Pacific Greyhound.","start":1076.032,"stop":1086.796,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But if Congress meant that, why wouldn't they say for any corporation authorized by the Commission to become a carrier to acquire control of another if it meant just that -- just what you said it means.","start":1086.796,"stop":1107.26,"duration":20.46}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would answer -- I would answer that in two ways.","start":1107.26,"stop":1110.158,"duration":2.9},{"text":"First, as this Court has recognized, Section 5 applies to such a variety of transactions, but this Court has never insisted that every transaction covered by Section 5 be spelled out in -- in quite that detail.","start":1110.158,"stop":1126.174,"duration":16.02},{"text":"And secondly, I would like -- I would like to show that the purposes, which Congress intended to be served by this control under Section 5 require that the Commission exercise control over this type of carrier split-up.","start":1126.174,"stop":1145.244,"duration":19.07},{"text":"Because in a -- in a number of cases under the Transportation Act of 1920, cases dealing with Section 5 and related provisions of the Act such of those of Section 20 (a), concerned with security issues that this Court has given a broad remedial sweep to these provisions.","start":1145.244,"stop":1169.268,"duration":24.02},{"text":"Thus, in the Schwabacher case, you summarized your prior decisions as confirming the power and duty of the Interstate Commerce Commission regardless of state law to control rate and capital structures, physical make up and relations between carriers, in the light of the public interest and an efficient -- in an efficient national transportation system.","start":1169.268,"stop":1194.564,"duration":25.3},{"text":"Now, turning to what we think is the leading case in the interpretation of Section 5, the New York Central Securities Corporation case in 287 U.S.","start":1194.564,"stop":1204.168,"duration":9.6},{"text":"Now, that case involved Section 5 as it read in the Transportation Act of 1920.","start":1204.168,"stop":1210.041,"duration":5.87},{"text":"And at that time, so far as here pertinent, Section 5 then -- then authorized a carrier with the prior approval of the Commission to acquire control of another carrier by lease or by purchase of stock.","start":1210.041,"stop":1224.249,"duration":14.21},{"text":"And in that case, the Commission had authorized a carrier to list the properties of two carriers, which it already controlled through stock ownership.","start":1224.249,"stop":1232.543,"duration":8.29},{"text":"And this Court held that the lease, despite the prior stock control, that the lease involved in acquisition of control, which require the Commission's approval under Section 5.","start":1232.543,"stop":1244.538,"duration":12},{"text":"And we think the gist of this Court's decision in that case appears in one short paragraph, which Your Honors quoted last term with approval in the Alleghany case, and I quote briefly, “The public interest is served by economy and efficiency in operation that the expected advantages are inadequately secured by stock ownership and will be better secured by lease.","start":1244.538,"stop":1266.144,"duration":21.61},{"text":"The statute affords no basis for the contention that the latter maybe authorized, although the former exist.”","start":1266.144,"stop":1273.238,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Then on the Alleghany case, this Court recognized what was not really an issue in that case.","start":1273.238,"stop":1279.84,"duration":6.6},{"text":"This Court recognized that approval under Section 5 is required for the merger of a wholly owned carrier corporation and to its carrier parent.","start":1279.84,"stop":1290.902,"duration":11.06},{"text":"But -- and in the Alleghany case, this Court said in determining, the test to determine, the test to apply in determining what transactions are subject to Section 5 is the crux of each inquiry to determine whether there has been an acquisition of control, is the nature of the change in relations between the companies, whose proposed transactions is before the Commission for approval.","start":1290.902,"stop":1318.406,"duration":27.5},{"text":"And the dissenting opinion on that case recognized that Section 5 applies to many intra-system transactions by carriers.","start":1318.406,"stop":1327.503,"duration":9.1},{"text":"So, we think the rationale of those two leading decisions under Section 5, both before and after the 1940 amendment, is that if a transaction results in a significant change in the control of relationship between carriers, then it's subject to Section 5.","start":1327.503,"stop":1342.784,"duration":15.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You said carriers.","start":1342.784,"stop":1343.867,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Did either one of them or did the Alleghany case will support your judgments to hold that the Section 5 applied where one was a carrier and one was not?","start":1343.867,"stop":1356.951,"duration":13.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, admittedly, Alleghany was dealing with an entirely different set of facts.","start":1356.951,"stop":1361.137,"duration":4.19},{"text":"I'm drawing on that only for --","start":1361.137,"stop":1362.543,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I just wondered if the -- if the (Inaudible)","start":1362.543,"stop":1367.419,"duration":4.88},{"text":"Has this Court ever approved application of Section 5, acquisition of one carrier over a non-carrier?","start":1367.419,"stop":1380.349,"duration":12.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":1380.349,"stop":1381.48,"duration":1.13},{"text":"Certainly -- certainly, the immediate issue in this case has never been before this Court or indeed before any federal court.","start":1381.48,"stop":1389.479,"duration":8},{"text":"And we think that such a -- such a --","start":1389.479,"stop":1391.117,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you --","start":1391.117,"stop":1391.607,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon, sir.","start":1391.607,"stop":1393.661,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you use the word \"carriers\" in all of these subdivisions in exactly the same way?","start":1393.661,"stop":1400.499,"duration":6.84},{"text":"Do you think wherever the word \"carrier\" appears in 1, 2, 3, 4 or 5 that it should be interpreted the way you have interpreted it for us here in -- in this particular subdivision?","start":1400.499,"stop":1424.2,"duration":23.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't thought all of that through frankly.","start":1424.2,"stop":1427.135,"duration":2.93},{"text":"I think the same definition would apply if what was being done here was not an acquisition of stock control, but if it were being done by lease or purchase of properties.","start":1427.135,"stop":1439.496,"duration":12.36},{"text":"As to whether that would be the same, it would always be the same, have the same meaning under the tremendous variety of -- of transactions which can arise under Section 5.","start":1439.496,"stop":1450.822,"duration":11.33},{"text":"I'm reluctant to be dogmatic.","start":1450.822,"stop":1452.968,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would you say that you conclude from that when -- that whenever Congress does use the word \"carrier\", you'll know it might be designedly that the -- the Interstate Commerce Commission has a right to determine when and -- and where it will consider that they must be carriers before -- before the proceeding or -- or whether they can wait until it's all over and -- and the Commission decides whether they want them to be carriers?","start":1452.968,"stop":1488.313,"duration":35.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, ultimately, the scope of it is -- is determined by the courts.","start":1488.313,"stop":1497.377,"duration":9.06},{"text":"The Commission has not had occasion to deal with -- that I can think of with any other situation in which it had to -- in which it looked at the consummation of a transaction to determine who was a carrier.","start":1497.377,"stop":1517.297,"duration":19.92},{"text":"This type of situation, and we cite four or five identical situations in other cases before the Commission, is the only thing in that area that I'm aware of, in other words, a split-up of -- of different types of carrier operations into separate carrier entities.","start":1517.297,"stop":1536.501,"duration":19.2},{"text":"It's the only thing I know of that we had to deal with (Inaudible)","start":1536.501,"stop":1539.345,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"From the point of view of the Commission, what are the practical consequences of withholding that there is no jurisdiction in a case like this?","start":1539.345,"stop":1549.419,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Historically, I would have to say that this has not been a -- a major thing in the Commission's work.","start":1549.419,"stop":1557.423,"duration":8},{"text":"There is this case and the four or five prior cases cited and -- and cited in our brief.","start":1557.423,"stop":1563.858,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Some of them referred to by the appellants.","start":1563.858,"stop":1567.987,"duration":4.13},{"text":"There have been five or six cases at the most since 1940.","start":1567.987,"stop":1573.122,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Forecasting, what difficulties do you see holding that you have got jurisdiction?","start":1573.122,"stop":1580.97,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a -- is a dangerous time in history for prediction in the field of transportation.","start":1580.97,"stop":1585.893,"duration":4.92},{"text":"As Your Honors probably know, we're in the middle of a transportation revolution, reassessment of the respective roles of different -- different types of carriers, new -- new ratemaking techniques, new types of equipment.","start":1585.893,"stop":1603.669,"duration":17.78},{"text":"Whether the -- whether the -- this type of situation would arise more frequently or less frequently in the future, I can't give you an honest opinion, one that's worth anything.","start":1603.669,"stop":1612.673,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) you have jurisdiction to (Inaudible) commuter services for example are unprofitable.","start":1612.673,"stop":1632.211,"duration":19.54}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I have speculated about the same thing frankly.","start":1632.211,"stop":1637.327,"duration":5.12},{"text":"It hasn't been out so far.","start":1637.327,"stop":1638.895,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose if this is (Inaudible) in this case, it might (Inaudible) some analysis (Inaudible)","start":1638.895,"stop":1654.438,"duration":15.54}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I can -- I can only guess, sir.","start":1654.438,"stop":1656.142,"duration":1.7},{"text":"I -- I have speculated.","start":1656.142,"stop":1658.557,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ginnane, do you have to depend for -- to charge of the Commission on the purchase, words of (Inaudible) should be lawful with approval and authorization of the Commission as provided in subdivision (b) for two or more carriers to consolidate or merge?","start":1658.557,"stop":1678.365,"duration":19.81}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1678.365,"stop":1678.743,"duration":0.38},{"text":"We -- we rely on the clause a bit later for any carrier or two or more carriers jointly to acquire control of another through ownership of its stock or otherwise.","start":1678.743,"stop":1689.946,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"There's another carrier?","start":1689.946,"stop":1691.186,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1691.186,"stop":1692.686,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that thing [Laughs] is disturbed in our case unless both of these were carriers.","start":1692.686,"stop":1702.134,"duration":9.45},{"text":"What adequate information you get through this?","start":1702.134,"stop":1705.974,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Because at the end of the transaction, both are admittedly carriers.","start":1705.974,"stop":1710.663,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But when they saw it, they're not.","start":1710.663,"stop":1713.94,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1713.94,"stop":1714.044,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I presume this meant that -- I -- I presume it meant but it sounds like it meant that somebody could at least two carriers could initiate it or one could initiate it, the action to get control of the other.","start":1714.044,"stop":1727.166,"duration":13.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"And certainly, that has been the typical case.","start":1727.166,"stop":1730.972,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Now, what the Commission did here in substance was to authorize Pacific Greyhound to segregate into separate corporate carrier entities, its short-haul commuter operations on the one hand, and at long haul, intercity operations on the other.","start":1730.972,"stop":1747.004,"duration":16.03},{"text":"And on the series of prior decisions beginning in 1940, the Commission has done exactly that same sort of thing to authorize carriers, to segregate substantially different types of carrier operations.","start":1747.004,"stop":1761.469,"duration":14.47},{"text":"Now, they are summarized in our brief at pages 15 and 20, but I can just pinpoint each of them now.","start":1761.469,"stop":1767.707,"duration":6.24},{"text":"In the Columbia Motor Service case, there was involved a separation of contract carrier from common carrier operations.","start":1767.707,"stop":1774.946,"duration":7.24},{"text":"In Consolidated Freightways, it was a separation of the transportation of automobiles with special equipment from the transportation of general commodities in the -- in the ordinary equipment.","start":1774.946,"stop":1785.486,"duration":10.54},{"text":"The Takin case involves the segregation of interstate transportation of general commodities from intrastate transportation of household goods.","start":1785.486,"stop":1794.269,"duration":8.78},{"text":"And the Gehlhaus case involved a segregation of motor carrier operations from water carrier operations.","start":1794.269,"stop":1800.396,"duration":6.13},{"text":"And all those cases, the Commission recognized that the different management and operating problems of the distinctly different types of transportation warranted their segregation into separate operations -- into separate corporations.","start":1800.396,"stop":1816.865,"duration":16.47},{"text":"At the same time, the Commission feels and I submit that such a division of a carrier's operations and no matter how useful, no matter how helpful it may be in terms of more efficient transportation, there's something that cannot be done without control, without regulation because the resulting division of assets, how that's done is crucial to the ability of each of the -- of the succeeding corporations to -- to serve the public.","start":1816.865,"stop":1846.385,"duration":29.52},{"text":"It relates to -- well, it can affect their credit standing and other matters with which Congress intended the Commission to concern itself in exercising its powers under Section 5.","start":1846.385,"stop":1859.164,"duration":12.78},{"text":"So we think that what the Commission did in this case and the type of thing the Commission did here in authorizing a division of carrier operations, as it did on these other -- in these prior cases is consistent, not only with the letter of Section 5 to which we don't attach so much weight but to the broad purposes of Section 5, which this Court has recognized again and again.","start":1859.164,"stop":1887.01,"duration":27.85},{"text":"In brief, that it's in the interest of economic transportation that carriers would be able to do this depending upon the circumstances to -- to divide clearly different types of transportation operations in a -- in a separate corporate entities.","start":1887.01,"stop":1905.007,"duration":18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course we don't have the right of the Commission before us.","start":1905.007,"stop":1907.952,"duration":2.94},{"text":"But is there findings (Inaudible) on its own list, as I understand it, large community service has the better chance of possibly in -- in the public interest of its own (Inaudible) and enacted with the -- the way now it is in the general operations?","start":1907.952,"stop":1926.102,"duration":18.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the Commission made -- the Commission did not make a finding in those terms.","start":1926.102,"stop":1929.74,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would suppose underlying all this is more economic transportation for the overall public benefit.","start":1929.74,"stop":1939.726,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1939.726,"stop":1939.961,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) consideration which leads to the approving this kind of thing.","start":1939.961,"stop":1944.153,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"And the Commission detailed at some length in its report --","start":1944.153,"stop":1947.716,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, necessarily, that might --","start":1947.716,"stop":1949.307,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the separate types of management problems involved between the long-haul transportation and the short-haul commuter operation.","start":1949.307,"stop":1955.199,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) some judgment though that at least this particular community service is not going to be impaired by this separation from the general operation?","start":1955.199,"stop":1966.318,"duration":11.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Commission discussed the matter at length in its report.","start":1966.318,"stop":1968.673,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's it but we don't have it now.","start":1968.673,"stop":1970.077,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the Commission's report is printed as a part of the record, but not -- but not on the underlying evidence is printed there.","start":1970.077,"stop":1976.154,"duration":6.08},{"text":"And we submit that in the present posture of the case, all it's before the Court is the -- is the general -- almost academic question of the Commission's power -- jurisdiction to -- to authorize this type of thing, this general type of thing, this -- what the appellants call a split-up under Section 5 of the underlying merits, which certainly could have been challenged by these appellants.","start":1976.154,"stop":2000.824,"duration":24.67},{"text":"They could have challenged it, the Commission's action as an abuse of discretion.","start":2000.824,"stop":2005.25,"duration":4.43},{"text":"All those things which could have been raised, haven't been raised, haven't been presented to the court below or to this Court.","start":2005.25,"stop":2011.867,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand why you say academic.","start":2011.867,"stop":2014.385,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I don't mean academic.","start":2014.385,"stop":2017.011,"duration":2.63},{"text":"But it's here just as a general question --","start":2017.011,"stop":2019.932,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":2019.932,"stop":2020.321,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whether we -- as to whether we can -- the --","start":2020.321,"stop":2022.451,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Will you have any power though?","start":2022.451,"stop":2022.637,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Commission can authorize this type of transaction.","start":2022.637,"stop":2024.722,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Will you have any power at all?","start":2024.722,"stop":2025.98,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's what I meant to say, sir.","start":2025.98,"stop":2029.031,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Now, I have said that this precise issue hasn't been considered by the federal courts.","start":2029.031,"stop":2035.431,"duration":6.4},{"text":"There are two cases, which I find a little difficult to understand but which -- which at least deal with similar questions.","start":2035.431,"stop":2045.822,"duration":10.39},{"text":"They are cited in our brief, their decisions of the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit and for the District of Columbia Circuit are dealing with the similar consolidation provisions of the -- of the Civil Aeronautics Act.","start":2045.822,"stop":2060.819,"duration":15},{"text":"Those decisions of those two Courts of Appeals at least stand for the proposition that in determining whether for the purpose of such statutory provisions, one carrier has acquired control of another carrier.","start":2060.819,"stop":2075.553,"duration":14.73},{"text":"The agency should look to see what the result is at the consummation of the transaction.","start":2075.553,"stop":2080.721,"duration":5.17},{"text":"The facts in those cases were somewhat different than this, so we cannot cite them as cases in point.","start":2080.721,"stop":2086.866,"duration":6.14},{"text":"We do -- we do refer Your Honors to the reasoning from those cases, which are set forth at some detail in our briefs.","start":2086.866,"stop":2094.161,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they have the same legislative history with the -- with the provisions of the CAB proposed in Congress for the same reasons that -- that this section was proposed for?","start":2094.161,"stop":2113.122,"duration":18.96}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we can say generally they were because they are practically forbidden, whole -- the whole paragraphs of the section are -- are verbatim -- verbatim list and the provisions of Section 5 of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2113.122,"stop":2125.074,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But wasn't -- wasn't the -- the provision in the Civil Aeronautics Act more for the purpose of -- of protecting against monopoly and on the other hand, these provisions more for the purpose of -- of relieving the railroads from some of the stringent antitrust regulations and making it easier for them to merge in order to take care of -- of the sick industry where the other was rebutting industry and they want to keep the lines straight so there would be ample competition?","start":2125.074,"stop":2168.236,"duration":43.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"There is some element of such distinction.","start":2168.236,"stop":2170.213,"duration":1.98},{"text":"I wouldn't know how far to go in -- in making such a distinction.","start":2170.213,"stop":2175.138,"duration":4.92},{"text":"For example, there is a -- a declaration of policy in that Act which puts a much heavier emphasis on the value of competition in their transportation than anything which appears in the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2175.138,"stop":2188.913,"duration":13.78},{"text":"I would like to refer only briefly to the appellant's contention that as a -- apparent contention that as a matter of law, the Commission should not so act under Section 5 as to affect intrastate operating rights which are subject to regulation by State Commissions.","start":2188.913,"stop":2208.645,"duration":19.73},{"text":"But Your Honors have passed upon that general type of question again and again in -- in questions in cases interpreting Paragraph 11 of Section 5.","start":2208.645,"stop":2217.885,"duration":9.24},{"text":"Now, Paragraph 11 says that upon approval of a transaction by the Commission, the participating carriers may carry it out without regard to the limitations of federal, state or municipal law and specifically that they may exercise any control or franchises acquired through such transaction.","start":2217.885,"stop":2239.012,"duration":21.13},{"text":"Your Honors have -- have considered that so many times and interpret it, so -- and applied it so broadly and literally that I think we do not need to labor it here.","start":2239.012,"stop":2250.89,"duration":11.88},{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2250.89,"stop":2260.692,"duration":9.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Avakian -- oh, pardon me.","start":2260.692,"stop":2262.683,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":2262.683,"stop":2266.88,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Matthew.","start":2266.88,"stop":2270.587,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2270.587,"stop":2274.965,"duration":4.38},{"text":"The time remaining is quite brief and yet I do wish to say a few things on both of the two issues which are before the Court at this time.","start":2274.965,"stop":2286.482,"duration":11.52},{"text":"I must be brief.","start":2286.482,"stop":2287.338,"duration":0.86},{"text":"I realized that perhaps it can be little more than a summary but first dealing with this jurisdictional issue.","start":2287.338,"stop":2295.317,"duration":7.98},{"text":"May I say that I think I would respond to the question posed by the Chief Justice and other Justices as to what particular language of the section is that upon which we rely to validate this particular transaction.","start":2295.317,"stop":2313.879,"duration":18.56},{"text":"I would refer it by Section 5 (11), a text appearing upon page 5 -- 15 rather of our brief for the appellees, Golden Gate Transit Lines, et al, and now, I just briefly read, “The authority conferred by this section shall be exclusive and plenary, and any carrier or corporation participating in or resulting from any transaction approved by the Commission thereunder, shall have full power,\" and so forth.","start":2313.879,"stop":2345.207,"duration":31.33}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's in the large 5 brief, isn't it?","start":2345.207,"stop":2347.431,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I think it defined just what is in Section 5 and it does apply to resulting (Inaudible) and I have had no doubt and I examined the provision of the statute time and time again.","start":2347.431,"stop":2358.545,"duration":11.11},{"text":"And it seems to me that Congress was at particular pains to button up and complete this jurisdiction to the Commission, so that there'll be no means to escape from it.","start":2358.545,"stop":2369.581,"duration":11.04},{"text":"And we venture to say upon our brief here that we can't conceive any language as a more comprehensive and get so specific.","start":2369.581,"stop":2377.491,"duration":7.91},{"text":"Now, clearly, we do have a carrier which will result from the transaction which the Commission has approved.","start":2377.491,"stop":2384.227,"duration":6.74},{"text":"I think that's right within the expressed terms of the statute.","start":2384.227,"stop":2387.646,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Now, we carry forward just a bit.","start":2387.646,"stop":2390.404,"duration":2.76},{"text":"This is an intra-system transaction.","start":2390.404,"stop":2395.01,"duration":4.61},{"text":"These are words frequently used by this Court.","start":2395.01,"stop":2398.257,"duration":3.25},{"text":"The -- it is not to the course that these provisions of the statute deal only with mergers and consolidations.","start":2398.257,"stop":2408.609,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Granting of that was the main objective, objective as of the legislation as it has been developed here thus far.","start":2408.609,"stop":2417.559,"duration":8.95},{"text":"The statute does not restricted to that but covers all manual acquisitions and specifically some purely intra-system transactions.","start":2417.559,"stop":2428.931,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Now, the transaction, which was authorized by the Commission and approved by this Court in the New York Central Securities case, was nothing but an intra-system transaction and is observed by -- in the dissenting opinion of Mr. Justice Douglas in the Alleghany case, in commenting upon the decision in the New York Security -- Central Securities case.","start":2428.931,"stop":2449.407,"duration":20.48},{"text":"It is said that Section 5 (2) (a) requires many, many intra-system transactions to be subject to the approval of the Commission and that was too here.","start":2449.407,"stop":2460.627,"duration":11.22},{"text":"Now, Mr. Ginnane has referred to the language used by this Court in the Schwabacher case, which we think is very significant because we have there set forth in a single sentence what I may call the basic philosophy of these provisions alone.","start":2460.627,"stop":2479.781,"duration":19.15},{"text":"And I briefly read that one sentence again, “The tenure of all of this was to confirm the power and duty of the Interstate Commerce Commission, regardless of state law to control rate and capital structures, physical makeup and relation to tin carriers in the light of the public interest in an efficient national transportation system.”","start":2479.781,"stop":2504.281,"duration":24.5},{"text":"Neither can be no doubt that this immediate program which the Commission approved in our case, this transaction is within the precise times, as I read it, of this declaration of basic policy in the opinion of this Court in the Schwabacher case.","start":2504.281,"stop":2523.171,"duration":18.89},{"text":"I could continue beyond it but I think that's all that I need.","start":2523.171,"stop":2526.808,"duration":3.64},{"text":"I -- I want to act to this great equation as to the possible consequences of a ruling here that this transaction is enough to the jurisdiction of the Commission.","start":2526.808,"stop":2538.288,"duration":11.48},{"text":"There would be a very unfortunate jurisdictional void of these particular carriers, the Greyhound, if you please, or a real carrier could form a subsidiary corporation to be controlled by it and transfer to that carrier such properties as it might desire and could transfer to it stock in other corporations, thus seeking the approval of the Commission.","start":2538.288,"stop":2569.115,"duration":30.83},{"text":"Now, the Commission has brought that out in its brief here and said so in several decisions, there'll be a void if a transaction to this immediate character were not subject to the Commission's control.","start":2569.115,"stop":2582.192,"duration":13.08},{"text":"Now, there's much more that I would like to say on that jurisdictional question but I think I have enough time, but I do want to answer an inquiry that came from Mr. Justice Brennan, I believe, as to the findings of the Commission as to how the carriers would function under this transaction as authorized.","start":2582.192,"stop":2602.563,"duration":20.37},{"text":"The opinion of the Commission is here.","start":2602.563,"stop":2604.262,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Of course, the record before the Commission is not here.","start":2604.262,"stop":2607.207,"duration":2.94},{"text":"It was not before the lower court as has been stated.","start":2607.207,"stop":2610.104,"duration":2.9},{"text":"I am not free to discuss anything in that record.","start":2610.104,"stop":2613.031,"duration":2.93},{"text":"Those issues, many of them and not before this Court now, but we asked the Court in particular to review what the Commission says upon pages 17 to 18 of -- no, we passed that, pardon me, and I correct that, upon pages 27 to 28 in particular of its opinion.","start":2613.031,"stop":2636.324,"duration":23.29},{"text":"There starting with the -- well, I say the paragraph at the middle of that page 27, where the Commission addresses itself to the public interest in the national transportation policy and then where the paragraph commencing toward the bottom of that page, it deals with the whole problem which was here before the Commission in dealing with these local operations and briefly points out, and I'll just mentioned this, briefly refers in the third line of that last paragraph to the impractical retention in a single entity of how the similar operation it is on, then it deals with the services which will be left.","start":2636.324,"stop":2674.409,"duration":38.09},{"text":"All of this will be subdivided on page 28 then further on page -- I'll just briefly refer to this, 31.","start":2674.409,"stop":2682.749,"duration":8.34},{"text":"It makes these findings as to consistency to the public convenience and necessity.","start":2682.749,"stop":2688.052,"duration":5.3},{"text":"I can't comment beyond that and I again will point out, there's just one issue here we're dealing with in this branch of the case and that is the issue of jurisdiction.","start":2688.052,"stop":2696.617,"duration":8.57},{"text":"It was jurisdiction in the Commission to authorize this transaction.","start":2696.617,"stop":2700.8,"duration":4.18},{"text":"We submit that it was and that it be ghastly against the public interest if that jurisdiction we held not to exist there.","start":2700.8,"stop":2708.611,"duration":7.81},{"text":"Now, just a few words about the effort to amend this complaint, there would be no much understanding as to the circumstances there.","start":2708.611,"stop":2716.336,"duration":7.72},{"text":"We have not contend it and I'm not quite sure Mr. Ginnane has not given the Court the impression that under all conditions, a complaint attacking an order of the Interstate Commerce Commission and seeking its annulment should not be subject to amendment.","start":2716.336,"stop":2732.793,"duration":16.46},{"text":"In proper case, there might be, but the Congress has made it very clear and this is spelled out so carefully in the opinion of Mr. Justice Brandeis for the anonymous court in the Griffin case in 303 United States that I'm sure are not to be overlooked.","start":2732.793,"stop":2751.911,"duration":19.12},{"text":"It gives us the history of these rules for expedited procedure in dealing with complaints brought to in all orders, the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":2751.911,"stop":2762.179,"duration":10.27},{"text":"It points out that they originated in 1903 with statutes to enforce the Antitrust Act or opposing it.","start":2762.179,"stop":2771.649,"duration":9.47},{"text":"And then in 1906 by the Hepburn Act, they were extended of the Interstate Commerce Commissioner.","start":2771.649,"stop":2776.839,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Then in 1910, when the Commerce Court is created, they were continued in effect.","start":2776.839,"stop":2782.615,"duration":5.78},{"text":"Some 20 years later when the Commerce Court was abolished, they were still continue to effect under the terms of the Urgent Deficiencies Act.","start":2782.615,"stop":2789.528,"duration":6.91},{"text":"And Mr. Justice Brandeis -- Brandeis makes it exceedingly here, so clear that surely we ought not to disregard them at all, and I'm quoting in, referring to these expedited procedures.","start":2789.528,"stop":2801.515,"duration":11.99},{"text":"He says, “These expedited procedures in suits by the United States -- pardon me just a moment.","start":2801.515,"stop":2808.095,"duration":6.58},{"text":"“These extradited procedures -- pardon me.","start":2808.095,"stop":2811.616,"duration":3.52},{"text":"I'm trying to go along too hasty I guess.","start":2811.616,"stop":2814.107,"duration":2.49},{"text":"The Court says and this is quoted upon page 41 of the Commission's brief here that -- and I'm quoting, “Upon both the trial court and the Supreme Court rest the obligation to give the case precedence over others.”","start":2814.107,"stop":2826.459,"duration":12.35},{"text":"And he says further and I again quote it, “In such cases, Congress sought to guard against ill-conceited action by a single judge and to avert delays ordinarily instant litigation.”","start":2826.459,"stop":2838.321,"duration":11.86},{"text":"So that Congress in this type of case has particularly undertook to guard against the very sorted length that our adversaries thought to impose upon us in this case.","start":2838.321,"stop":2848.349,"duration":10.03},{"text":"Now, just a few words about the chronology of this case if my time is not expired.","start":2848.349,"stop":2853.328,"duration":4.98},{"text":"That chronology has some importance.","start":2853.328,"stop":2856.383,"duration":3.05},{"text":"The Court will bear in mind that the order of the Commission was entered on July 6, 1955.","start":2856.383,"stop":2862.098,"duration":5.72},{"text":"It was already nearly three years old incidentally.","start":2862.098,"stop":2864.983,"duration":2.89},{"text":"On October 18, 1955, the complaint to annul the order was filed in the District Court in San Francisco.","start":2864.983,"stop":2871.368,"duration":6.38},{"text":"On February 17, 1956, appellant's motion for the judgment on the pleadings was filed, following motion for judgment in pleadings by the Government and motion to dismiss on our part.","start":2871.368,"stop":2883.829,"duration":12.46},{"text":"Now, on February 28, 1956, where the appellant's motion relieved to amend the complaint.","start":2883.829,"stop":2891.33,"duration":7.5},{"text":"That is only 11 days after he had pleaded for judgment on the pleadings.","start":2891.33,"stop":2895.477,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Now, let's turn to the transcript just a moment, if we have that much time.","start":2895.477,"stop":2900.879,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Page 17, we have -- I think it's page 17, the appellant's motion for leave to -- pardon me, motion for judgment on the pleadings filed February 17, 1956, commencing at the fifth line at the bottom.","start":2900.879,"stop":2918.96,"duration":18.08},{"text":"It is alleged, there is no question of fact involved in the case and the sole question presented is one of law, which should be determined in favor of the prejudice.","start":2918.96,"stop":2928.385,"duration":9.43},{"text":"Therefore, he was entitled to judgment on the pleadings.","start":2928.385,"stop":2930.858,"duration":2.47},{"text":"We turn over pages -- just to page 74.","start":2930.858,"stop":2934.133,"duration":3.27},{"text":"On pages 74 to 78 inclusive, we have his motion where leave to amend his complaint filed only 11 days after he filed his motion for judgment on the pleadings.","start":2934.133,"stop":2945.527,"duration":11.39},{"text":"I want to answer one further question that came from the Chief Justice.","start":2945.527,"stop":2948.93,"duration":3.4},{"text":"When appellant's counsel made the first suggestion to the Court at the opening of the hearing on February 23rd, it's the first time he suggested it that if the Court was going to rule against him on his jurisdictional issues, he want to leave to amend -- pardon me.","start":2948.93,"stop":2963.952,"duration":15.02},{"text":"Must I stop?","start":2963.952,"stop":2965.633,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Your time is up, Mr. Matthew.","start":2965.633,"stop":2967.579,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I just complete that one sentence?","start":2967.579,"stop":2969.427,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, you may complete your sentence.","start":2969.427,"stop":2971.025,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2971.025,"stop":2971.712,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":2971.712,"stop":2973.055,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Allan P. Matthew","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't want to leave any misunderstanding, that's all.","start":2973.055,"stop":2977.081,"duration":4.03},{"text":"When the -- I'm sorry, but he made the suggestion that the Court might rule against him on the jurisdiction.","start":2977.081,"stop":2984.421,"duration":7.34},{"text":"He wants leave to amend his complaint.","start":2984.421,"stop":2986.261,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Certainly, Judge Healy is very improperly observed that the judgment could not be made in that form, his constant desire to amend to file his motion to amend.","start":2986.261,"stop":2996.378,"duration":10.12},{"text":"I'm sorry to (Inaudible) with my time.","start":2996.378,"stop":2998.098,"duration":1.72},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":2998.098,"stop":2998.129,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It's all right.","start":2998.129,"stop":3003.166,"duration":5.04},{"text":"Mr. Avakian.","start":3003.166,"stop":3018.591,"duration":15.42}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":3018.591,"stop":3019.53,"duration":0.94},{"text":"I'd like to refer once again to the circumstances under which the amendment to the complaint was offered.","start":3019.53,"stop":3028.161,"duration":8.63},{"text":"In the Interstate Commerce Commission report at page 21 of the record, there is this statement regarding one of the public interest reasons which impelled the Commission to authorize this transaction.","start":3028.161,"stop":3044.094,"duration":15.93},{"text":"Part of the overall management problem is that of labor management relations, which, although strongly disputed by the union, applicants contend with benefit from the proposed separation of the operations.","start":3044.094,"stop":3058.315,"duration":14.22},{"text":"The negotiation of employment contracts with the union in the past has been made especially difficult because the terms applicable to the two classes of drivers have been embraced in a single labor agreement even though the operating practices have been different.","start":3058.315,"stop":3076.572,"duration":18.26},{"text":"And then the report goes on to point to a strike situation which resulted because of conditions peculiar to one group but involving the entire system.","start":3076.572,"stop":3087.339,"duration":10.77},{"text":"Now, in the phase of that finding, Greyhound and Golden Gate on February 21, 1956 negotiated an agreement with the labor unions who, up to that point, were joint parties plaintiff with us.","start":3087.339,"stop":3103.918,"duration":16.58},{"text":"And that agreement provided that if this transaction went through, the employees of Golden Gate and Greyhound would be covered by a single labor agreement.","start":3103.918,"stop":3120.247,"duration":16.33},{"text":"Now, it was this strange circumstance on February 21, announced to the Court on February 23, that led the appellants immediately to reevaluate the question as to whether or not the public interest findings of the Commission should be challenged and appellants immediately made oral request for a permission to amend.","start":3120.247,"stop":3146.113,"duration":25.87},{"text":"And as Mr. Matthew has just stated, the Court gave permission to file a written motion with the proposed amendment in writing and that was done five days later, a weekend having intervened.","start":3146.113,"stop":3162.365,"duration":16.25},{"text":"Those were the circumstances that led to the motion to amend.","start":3162.365,"stop":3165.992,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"How long was that, the date of the complaint?","start":3165.992,"stop":3168.406,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The complaint had been filed on October 18.","start":3168.406,"stop":3171.867,"duration":3.46},{"text":"The answer of the United States had been filed on December 15.","start":3171.867,"stop":3176.982,"duration":5.11},{"text":"The intervention of Greyhound and Golden Gate had come about in January of 1956.","start":3176.982,"stop":3185.218,"duration":8.24},{"text":"The --","start":3185.218,"stop":3187.702,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"When was your -- your statement to the Court that you may want to amend on the -- when is that with reference to the complaint?","start":3187.702,"stop":3197.602,"duration":9.9}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Complaint was filed October 1855 and our oral request for permission to amend was February 23rd, immediately upon the announcement to the Court of the contract between the labor unions and --","start":3197.602,"stop":3212.771,"duration":15.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you think that was so relevant to this problem immediately after the labor union pulled out of the litigation?","start":3212.771,"stop":3218.681,"duration":5.91},{"text":"Why is that relevant and say you haven't urge that point?","start":3218.681,"stop":3221.911,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the relevance to me, Your Honor, is this.","start":3221.911,"stop":3225.369,"duration":3.46},{"text":"A -- a challenge to the public interest findings of the Interstate Commerce Commission raises a question which, from the appellant's point of view, is a very difficult one because the Court must be persuaded that there is no substantial basis in the record, none of the grounds set forth in -- in the Commission's findings are substantial and supported by the evidence.","start":3225.369,"stop":3250.693,"duration":25.32},{"text":"And if there is one substantial factor which would support the Commission's order, a challenge based on the -- on the adequacy of the findings will not succeed.","start":3250.693,"stop":3263.335,"duration":12.64},{"text":"And very frankly, the one factor which troubled me when I initially made the judgment decision not to challenge the findings was this question of the Interstate Commerce Commission's conclusion which recited a strike that the public interest would be served by having separate labor agreements.","start":3263.335,"stop":3284.492,"duration":21.16},{"text":"Now, this was rather dramatically exposed to me as a sham presentation which Greyhound and Golden Gate had made to the Interstate Commerce Commission and had successfully sold to the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":3284.492,"stop":3298.715,"duration":14.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but I don't see how the withdrawal by the union of their position in the litigation exposed the sham.","start":3298.715,"stop":3306.524,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't the withdrawal, it was the entering of the --","start":3306.524,"stop":3308.482,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you suppose the sham?","start":3308.482,"stop":3309.905,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The contract, the -- the contract that was entered into between the unions and Greyhound is what exposed it because that showed that Greyhound and Golden Gate realistically were not concerned about having a single labor agreement with both passes of Congress.","start":3309.905,"stop":3328.356,"duration":18.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that agreement showed to me that the union made a kind of arrangement that was satisfactory to do them.","start":3328.356,"stop":3332.879,"duration":4.52},{"text":"That's all it shows.","start":3332.879,"stop":3334.175,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, it was a satisfactory to them because as long as they could deal with -- on the single basis, that's all they were interested in.","start":3334.175,"stop":3340.505,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was the situation throughout this litigation from the time you filed your complaint in October.","start":3340.505,"stop":3346.204,"duration":5.7},{"text":"I'm not saying you are wrong but I don't see that -- that your justification doesn't seem to hitch with the conclusion.","start":3346.204,"stop":3351.913,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- I hope I can make myself clear that the thing that brought about the reevaluation in my mind of whether or not I should challenge the public interest finding and which led to the request for the amendment was that, in my judgment as a lawyer, I thought I could now possibly urge to the Court that there was no substantial basis for the public interest findings of the Commission.","start":3351.913,"stop":3379.333,"duration":27.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you were subject to such a private agreement between the union and the two corporations all through this theory.","start":3379.333,"stop":3387.148,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, because the Commission's finding was that the separation would result in their being separate labor agreements and that would be --","start":3387.148,"stop":3394.642,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but what --","start":3394.642,"stop":3394.91,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the public interest factor.","start":3394.91,"stop":3395.86,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- intervening event had nothing to do with the Commission's action.","start":3395.86,"stop":3399.382,"duration":3.52},{"text":"It had to do with the pursuit of self-interest by the labor union.","start":3399.382,"stop":3404.217,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that's certainly true, Your Honor.","start":3404.217,"stop":3406.447,"duration":2.23},{"text":"But the -- this brought about a completely different context in which to appraise the question of what challenge should be made to the Commission's findings.","start":3406.447,"stop":3415.728,"duration":9.28},{"text":"Now, this amendment came when the Court was first assembled to consider these motions for summary judgment.","start":3415.728,"stop":3425.496,"duration":9.77},{"text":"The argument on those motions for summary judgment is not waste of time if this amendment is granted because the amendment did not eliminate the statutory question from the case.","start":3425.496,"stop":3437.431,"duration":11.93},{"text":"The Court would still have had to concern itself with the question of whether Section 5 applied.","start":3437.431,"stop":3442.54,"duration":5.11},{"text":"So, there was no imposition on the time of the Court.","start":3442.54,"stop":3446.3,"duration":3.76},{"text":"The intervening --","start":3446.3,"stop":3448.191,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) imposition on the time of the Court but to take to that to go back, wasn't it?","start":3448.191,"stop":3452.999,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court --","start":3452.999,"stop":3453.335,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":3453.335,"stop":3453.959,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Court might have concluded as one possible outcome under our amendment to remand the case to the Commission for further consideration.","start":3453.959,"stop":3461.808,"duration":7.85},{"text":"That's a possibility.","start":3461.808,"stop":3465.062,"duration":3.25},{"text":"In view of the time which elapsed before the Court even ruled on our motion, 14 months after it was filed, I don't think it can be contended nor did the District Court state this is the ground, that delay was a reason for denial rather as it's already been brought out.","start":3465.062,"stop":3485.075,"duration":20.01},{"text":"The reason for the denial was that the applicable criteria were inadvertence mistake, excusable neglect and so on, the criteria for a relief from a default judgment rather than the standards which Rule 15 (a) requires.","start":3485.075,"stop":3501.257,"duration":16.18},{"text":"And I am rather shocked, I will say, to have heard Mr. Ginnane say here, and this is not set in their brief, to say here that Rule 15 (a) does not apply to proceedings for the review of Interstate Commerce Commission orders.","start":3501.257,"stop":3515.359,"duration":14.1},{"text":"If that -- the novel argument, I've never heard it suggested before.","start":3515.359,"stop":3519.865,"duration":4.51},{"text":"If Rule 15 (a) doesn't apply, then I don't know what rule does govern these proceedings.","start":3519.865,"stop":3526.336,"duration":6.47},{"text":"The important consideration that I would like to leave with the Court on this point is that just a month ago in the Spevack case, where the proposal to amend was made in the appellate court after the appellate court had decided the case, after the plaintiff had lost in two courts.","start":3526.336,"stop":3550.73,"duration":24.39},{"text":"The plaintiff then asked in the appellate court for leave to amend and was refused and this Court remanded that case back to the Court of Appeals to permit the amendment.","start":3550.73,"stop":3564.831,"duration":14.1},{"text":"With respect to the application of Section 5, I think it has been made clear that this transaction does not involve any change in the beneficial ownership of the carrier properties involved in this proceeding.","start":3564.831,"stop":3584.736,"duration":19.9},{"text":"This is not a situation where operating rights or carrier properties belonging to one carrier entity are being transferred to another carrier entity.","start":3584.736,"stop":3596.276,"duration":11.54},{"text":"This is not that type of situation.","start":3596.276,"stop":3598.779,"duration":2.5},{"text":"The beneficial ownership remains exactly the same.","start":3598.779,"stop":3602.103,"duration":3.32},{"text":"This is not even a case where there is a rearrangement within a single beneficial ownership of the -- the legal ownership, so as to -- to increase the degree of control, so that it could be argued that there is an acquisition of control in the sense of increase.","start":3602.103,"stop":3623.15,"duration":21.05},{"text":"This is not even that kind of a case.","start":3623.15,"stop":3625.172,"duration":2.02},{"text":"This is the kind of a case where we start with a single carrier and subdivide it into two.","start":3625.172,"stop":3632.653,"duration":7.48},{"text":"There is no clause of the statutory language which does not involve two carriers at the start.","start":3632.653,"stop":3643.84,"duration":11.19},{"text":"Now, the question was raised as to whether or not -- as what to the effect would be either as to the holding that Section 5 (2) applies or as to a holding that Section 5 (2) that does not apply.","start":3643.84,"stop":3663.522,"duration":19.68},{"text":"If this Court holds that Section 5 (2) applies to this kind of a split-up, then I venture to say that it will not take long for the transportation lawyers in the country to figure out that the same technique then can be used to sever from a single carrier operation a segment which is considered unprofitable and to do that with a complete bypassing of the State Commission which has jurisdiction over that segment.","start":3663.522,"stop":3696.837,"duration":33.32},{"text":"This Court has frequently held that a --","start":3696.837,"stop":3699.682,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3699.682,"stop":3703.588,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No, if the Section does not apply, then what is the problem?","start":3703.588,"stop":3706.451,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3706.451,"stop":3710.264,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Then the --","start":3710.264,"stop":3710.697,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3710.697,"stop":3713.081,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Then -- then in this situation, the intrastate operating rights could not be transferred without the approval of the State Commission.","start":3713.081,"stop":3721.731,"duration":8.65},{"text":"The I.C.C. under Section 212 could authorize the transfer only of the interstate operating rights involved and that where it comes then to the other facet of the question.","start":3721.731,"stop":3731.851,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Would a holding that Section 5 (2) is inapplicable to create any problems?","start":3731.851,"stop":3737.601,"duration":5.75},{"text":"Counsel for appellees talked about a jurisdictional void.","start":3737.601,"stop":3741.435,"duration":3.83},{"text":"There is no jurisdictional void because Section 212 (b) of the Interstate Commerce Act applying to motor carriers, which is set forth at page 6 of our main brief, says, “Except as provided in Section 5, any certificate or permit may be transferred pursuant to such rules and regulations as the Commission may prescribe.\"","start":3741.435,"stop":3770.662,"duration":29.23},{"text":"So that automatically, if Section 5 does not apply, the Commission still has jurisdiction as to the interstate rights under Section 212 (b), so there is no void in jurisdiction.","start":3770.662,"stop":3784.679,"duration":14.02},{"text":"There is no area of non-regulation.","start":3784.679,"stop":3786.889,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3786.889,"stop":3790.278,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, about -- not quite 6% of the traffic is interstate.","start":3790.278,"stop":3793.356,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3793.356,"stop":3794.178,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's right.","start":3794.178,"stop":3795.824,"duration":1.65},{"text":"So that we don't have this problem of creating a void in regulation.","start":3795.824,"stop":3801.454,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The general counsel for the Interstate Commerce Commission will presumably is in a better position than any of the rest of us to advise the Court as to what problems might arise, was powerless to set forth any problem which might be created.","start":3801.454,"stop":3815.964,"duration":14.51},{"text":"And it's clear that there can be done because there will still not be any possibility of manipulations without obtaining the authority of some commission, whatever commission has the jurisdiction.","start":3815.964,"stop":3834.938,"duration":18.97}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 09, 1958 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13484","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 415, County of Marin, County of Contra Costa, Marin County Federation of Commuters Club and the Contra Costa County Commuters versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":17.484,"duration":17.48},{"text":"Mr. Avakian.","start":17.484,"stop":19.741,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":19.741,"stop":21.845,"duration":2.1},{"text":"This case involves the question of whether the special machinery provided by Congress in Section 5 of the Interstate Commerce Act to encourage consolidations of carriers can be used for the slit up of a single carrier's operations into separate corporations for the purpose of escaping the regulatory policies applied by the State Utility Commission to the essentially intrastate operations involved in the split-up.","start":21.845,"stop":52.686,"duration":30.84},{"text":"It also raises the issue of whether it was an abuse of discretion to deny leave to amend the complaint to challenge the public interest findings of the Interstate Commerce Commission where the original complaint raised only the question of the applicability of the statute and the amendment was offered contemporaneously with the submission of cross-motions for summary judgment.","start":52.686,"stop":81.037,"duration":28.35},{"text":"The issue as to the applicability of Section 5 is of particular significance because of the interplay of federal state relationships in the regulation of local transportation services.","start":81.037,"stop":97.24,"duration":16.2},{"text":"The case is here on appeal from a judgment of a three-judge District Court affirming the order of the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":97.24,"stop":107.387,"duration":10.15},{"text":"That order, which was rendered in 1955, granted an application by Pacific Greyhound Lines and its newly created subsidiary, Golden Gate Transit Lines, to transfer Greyhound's local San Francisco Bay area operations to the new subsidiary, Golden Gate.","start":107.387,"stop":129.002,"duration":21.62},{"text":"The Interstate Commerce Commission held that Section 5 applied.","start":129.002,"stop":133.287,"duration":4.28},{"text":"This section provides that the transactions for the consolidation or merger or unification of carrier operations, either by acquisition of property or by arrangements for common control, must be first approved by the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":133.287,"stop":152.585,"duration":19.3},{"text":"And when so approved may be consummated without regard to the antitrust laws and without the approval of any other federal agency or of any state agency.","start":152.585,"stop":165.963,"duration":13.38},{"text":"If Section 5 does not apply to this transaction, then the Interstate Commerce Commission's authority is limited, under Section 212 (b), to a transfer of the interstate operating rights only and the State Commission would have jurisdiction over the proposed transfer of the intrastate service.","start":165.963,"stop":187.384,"duration":21.42},{"text":"In the District --","start":187.384,"stop":187.483,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the service in the San Francisco Bay area?","start":187.483,"stop":189.83,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"This service is in the San Francisco Bay area essentially a commuter service radiating out of San Francisco, a distance of 25 to 30 miles, northward into Marin Country, eastward into Contra Costa Country and southerly into what is known as the Peninsula area.","start":189.83,"stop":208.538,"duration":18.71},{"text":"In the District Court, the original complaint raised only the question of the applicability of Section 5.","start":208.538,"stop":216.48,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Both sides, that is plaintiffs and -- and the Government, made motions for summary judgment.","start":216.48,"stop":223.019,"duration":6.54},{"text":"Greyhound and Golden Gate, as interveners, filed a motion to amend and while those motions came up for argument, the appellants, who are here now, asked to leave to amend their complaint to challenge the public interest findings as well.","start":223.019,"stop":241.252,"duration":18.23},{"text":"The motion to amend was --","start":241.252,"stop":242.295,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- I'm sorry I miss something.","start":242.295,"stop":244.136,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Where was this motion to amend (Inaudible) something to make?","start":244.136,"stop":247.483,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"In the District Court.","start":247.483,"stop":248.324,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the District Court.","start":248.324,"stop":249.043,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":249.043,"stop":249.587,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":249.587,"stop":250.069,"duration":0.48},{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":250.069,"stop":252.359,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Just -- just a moment -- just a moment please.","start":252.359,"stop":254.681,"duration":2.32},{"text":"You may respond when your time comes.","start":254.681,"stop":256.706,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Mr. Attorney General","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":256.706,"stop":258.896,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may respond when your time comes.","start":258.896,"stop":261.482,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The denial of the motion to amend was by two of the judges.","start":261.482,"stop":265.876,"duration":4.39},{"text":"One of the members of the Court dissented on the ground that under Rule 15 (a) the amendment should be allowed in the interest of the --","start":265.876,"stop":273.451,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I -- may I ask this?","start":273.451,"stop":274.653,"duration":1.2},{"text":"This amendment was to one end?","start":274.653,"stop":277.302,"duration":2.65},{"text":"This is in the District Court, I believe --","start":277.302,"stop":278.463,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":278.463,"stop":278.818,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Commission had acted?","start":278.818,"stop":280.505,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":280.505,"stop":280.776,"duration":0.27},{"text":"And it was for the purpose of challenging the public interest findings of the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":280.776,"stop":286.311,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that issue contested before the Commission?","start":286.311,"stop":288.988,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, it was.","start":288.988,"stop":289.366,"duration":0.38},{"text":"It was contested before the Commission and it was contested on a petition for rehearing which the --","start":289.366,"stop":294.592,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the complaint -- in the complaint in which you challenged the order, no objection was made to that aspect of the order and in the District Court, we tried to amend the basis of -- for the extent and scope or the nature of the issues which you challenged, is that all?","start":294.592,"stop":313.07,"duration":18.48}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":313.07,"stop":313.329,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) in issue?","start":313.329,"stop":314.179,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":314.179,"stop":315.402,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Later than that, the only case (Inaudible)","start":315.402,"stop":320.641,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":320.641,"stop":321.381,"duration":0.74},{"text":"On the -- on the Section 5 point, that would control the case finally.","start":321.381,"stop":325.9,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":325.9,"stop":335.488,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Issue had been joined, Your Honor, by this cross-motions for summary judgment because the complaint raised only the legal question of the applicability of Section 5 but --","start":335.488,"stop":346.093,"duration":10.61}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":346.093,"stop":347.386,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"There had been an answer by the United States but not by the interveners.","start":347.386,"stop":351.64,"duration":4.25},{"text":"And I might add at this point that the complaint originally was not only by these appellants who are two commuter associations and two counties, but also joined as plaintiffs originally where the labor unions who represented Greyhound drivers.","start":351.64,"stop":367.978,"duration":16.34},{"text":"The motions for summary judgment and to dismiss were set for argument on February 23rd, 1956.","start":367.978,"stop":377.087,"duration":9.11},{"text":"When they were called, the interveners Greyhound and Golden Gate and the United States offered a dismissal by the labor union plaintiffs on the basis of an agreement which had been reached two days before February 21st.","start":377.087,"stop":394.644,"duration":17.56},{"text":"And that agreement contained the provision that if this transaction were consummated, the labor contract of the unions with the two carriers would be a single labor contract.","start":394.644,"stop":411.376,"duration":16.73},{"text":"This was directly contrary to one of the public interest findings of the Interstate Commerce Commission to the effect that one of the public interest factors which would be served by this separation was the separation of separate labor contracts for each operation and the Commission's order recited that there had been problems in the past by virtue of the fact that Greyhound had to deal with its local drivers in the same bargaining agreements as it did with its intercity drivers.","start":411.376,"stop":447.326,"duration":35.95},{"text":"And when this agreement, which resulted in the dismissal of the labor unions, was presented to the Court at the time the motions came up for argument, we stated to the Court that in view of this development and our reconsideration in the light of that of the issue of public interest, we desired leave to amend the complaint to raise also the issue of whether the evidence supported the public interest findings of the Commission.","start":447.326,"stop":479.076,"duration":31.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Since you fall into this, may I ask this?","start":479.076,"stop":482.511,"duration":3.44},{"text":"At the labor union, for them -- do they -- had they been before the Court?","start":482.511,"stop":488.258,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"As plaintiffs, yes.","start":488.258,"stop":489.189,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As plaintiffs.","start":489.189,"stop":489.957,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Jointly with us.","start":489.957,"stop":490.259,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And they -- and they raised the public interest question?","start":490.259,"stop":493.199,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"They had raised the public interest question before the Commission --","start":493.199,"stop":495.822,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So --","start":495.822,"stop":496.003,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but not before the Court.","start":496.003,"stop":497.245,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that although they had objected to the report and the determination of the Commission, they did not in court aline on your side objects to raise the public interest question, is that right?","start":497.245,"stop":511.396,"duration":14.15}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"They were -- they were exactly with us.","start":511.396,"stop":513.121,"duration":1.72},{"text":"There was a single complaint.","start":513.121,"stop":514.15,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they didn't raise the public interest question.","start":514.15,"stop":516.921,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":516.921,"stop":517.582,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":517.582,"stop":518.058,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"And we only raised it after they dismissed.","start":518.058,"stop":520.054,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But after they dismiss that the Commission having gone partly on the ground of its desirability, as I understand from you, of having two separate unions for bargaining purposes.","start":520.054,"stop":533.178,"duration":13.12},{"text":"The union itself in its answer did not raise that question but then, you keep it up after they dropped that although they have made no objection, is that right?","start":533.178,"stop":540.761,"duration":7.58},{"text":"Is that a fair statement?","start":540.761,"stop":541.895,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":541.895,"stop":542.949,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not going any --","start":542.949,"stop":543.069,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"It is essentially correct.","start":543.069,"stop":544.22,"duration":1.15},{"text":"The -- the only thing I'd like to say is that --","start":544.22,"stop":545.475,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not drawing any inference.","start":545.475,"stop":546.337,"duration":0.86},{"text":"I just want to know what it is.","start":546.337,"stop":547.697,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the unions were joint plaintiffs with us --","start":547.697,"stop":549.704,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":549.704,"stop":550.062,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in a single complaint.","start":550.062,"stop":550.688,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- (Voice Overlap) this point?","start":550.688,"stop":551.661,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Neither one of us raised it.","start":551.661,"stop":552.507,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":552.507,"stop":553.455,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":553.455,"stop":554.204,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that -- so that you -- you then made the point not because they have made them, there -- it was no longer there to raise it.","start":554.204,"stop":560.404,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":560.404,"stop":560.949,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":560.949,"stop":561.23,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"We made the point because this agreement as we saw this contrary to the finding of the Commission.","start":561.23,"stop":569.183,"duration":7.95},{"text":"The background of this case, if I may state it very briefly and the background is important because the -- a report of the Interstate Commerce Commission specifically recites that Greyhound's purpose in the slit-up is to escape the rate regulation policies of the California Public Utilities Commission.","start":569.183,"stop":592.248,"duration":23.07},{"text":"The background is essentially this.","start":592.248,"stop":593.922,"duration":1.67},{"text":"I've already stated the area covered.","start":593.922,"stop":596.099,"duration":2.18},{"text":"The population in that area is approximately 400,000 people.","start":596.099,"stop":601.236,"duration":5.14},{"text":"The revenue from this service which is proposed to be split off is approximately $3,700,000 a year.","start":601.236,"stop":610.101,"duration":8.87},{"text":"And of this revenue, 5.7% represents Interstate Commerce and 94.3% represents intrastate commerce.","start":610.101,"stop":623.166,"duration":13.07},{"text":"Greyhound's dissatisfaction with the State Public Utilities Commission is based on several factors.","start":623.166,"stop":631.585,"duration":8.42},{"text":"One is that in establishing rates for this local service, the State Public Utilities Commission has consistently held that Greyhound's revenue needs for this service should be determined in the light of its total intrastate revenues and that as long as Greyhound receives an adequate return in its total intrastate service, it is not entitled to an increase in rates in this particular segment.","start":631.585,"stop":663.101,"duration":31.52},{"text":"And I might say that in its rate decisions, the State Commission has allowed Greyhound a fair rate of return on its intrastate operations in the most recent decision in 1957, a 7.1% rate of return was allowed on the total intrastate service.","start":663.101,"stop":683.311,"duration":20.21},{"text":"In a decision in 1951, dealing with the statewide rates, a 6.4% rate of return was allowed.","start":683.311,"stop":692.287,"duration":8.98},{"text":"In applying this policy, the State Commission takes into consideration the fact that because of the necessity to preserve competition between Greyhound and others in other areas of the State, it is forced to establish rates in the other areas which give Greyhound more than a fair rate of return.","start":692.287,"stop":716.206,"duration":23.92},{"text":"And that windfall is offset in the State Commission's minds by the rates that it establishes in this local service.","start":716.206,"stop":725.131,"duration":8.92},{"text":"And the State Commission also states that it considers the law of diminishing returns with respect to increases in commuter rates and where it has given increases in this particular segment.","start":725.131,"stop":737.269,"duration":12.14},{"text":"It has felt that there was a limiting factor as to the amount of revenue which effectively could be obtained by an increase by reason of the diversion of traffic to carpools and other means of transportation that would result if the increases were too high.","start":737.269,"stop":755.645,"duration":18.38},{"text":"And finally, the carrier here, Greyhound, previously tried to get permission from the State Commission to transfer a portion of this service, the Marin Country portion, to another operator.","start":755.645,"stop":770.762,"duration":15.12},{"text":"And after a lengthy hearing, the State Commission held that the proposed financing of that transfer of a limited segment of this operation was insufficient, even though the transferee was proposing to invest $200,000 working capital in the operation.","start":770.762,"stop":791.386,"duration":20.62},{"text":"In this case, which involve not only Marin but Contra Costa and the Peninsula operation, Greyhound proposed to put into Golden Gate only $150,000 in working capital and the Interstate Commerce Commission conditioned its approval on the sum of only $250,000 as a working capital.","start":791.386,"stop":817.79,"duration":26.4},{"text":"After the Interstate Commerce Commission had rendered its decision in which it rejected the protest made by the labor unions and by the present appellants as to the applicability of Section 5 and as to the public interest, both groups, both the unions and the present appellants filed a petition for rehearing before the Commission in which they again challenged the applicability of Section 5.","start":817.79,"stop":845.129,"duration":27.34},{"text":"They challenged the public interest findings of the Commission and furthermore, they ask for further hearing because of some additional testimony which had been given after the Interstate Commerce Commission's decision.","start":845.129,"stop":859.394,"duration":14.26},{"text":"And I mention this because in the proposed amendment, we seek to charge abuse of discretion on the part of the Interstate Commerce Commission in denying this petition for further hearing.","start":859.394,"stop":872.436,"duration":13.04},{"text":"In the Interstate Commerce Commission proceeding, the --","start":872.436,"stop":875.465,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the parties challenge (Inaudible)","start":875.465,"stop":880.669,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"At all stages.","start":880.669,"stop":881.374,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"At all stages.","start":881.374,"stop":882.073,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":882.073,"stop":884.632,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What were the effects of the proposed amendment to be now that were allowed?","start":884.632,"stop":888.653,"duration":4.02},{"text":"Did you go back to the Court and argue exceptions to the findings of the Commission?","start":888.653,"stop":893.94,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":893.94,"stop":894.286,"duration":0.35},{"text":"We would argue the sufficiency of the evidence to support those findings and we would argue the question of abuse of discretion in denying the further hearing in view of the facts which I'm just about to state.","start":894.286,"stop":905.999,"duration":11.71},{"text":"In the Interstate Commerce Commission, the principal Greyhound witness testified that $150,000 cash working capital would be adequate for the subsidiary to perform the services.","start":905.999,"stop":918.686,"duration":12.69},{"text":"This was in the phase of the own showing of the carriers, that the one year's operation would produce a loss of $230,000.","start":918.686,"stop":932.407,"duration":13.72},{"text":"Two weeks after the Interstate Commerce Commission order had been handed down, this same witness, testifying before the State Utilities Commission in a proceeding seeking an increase in rates for the -- for the Marin and Peninsula services, testified that there should be included in the rate base or rate-making purposes, the item of cash working capital in an amount equal to one-twelfth of the annual cash expenditures.","start":932.407,"stop":967.586,"duration":35.18},{"text":"And in the examination in that case, he said most emphatically that this was a necessary working capital.","start":967.586,"stop":975.036,"duration":7.45},{"text":"He even said that a new company would have to provide that much capital.","start":975.036,"stop":980.577,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Now, as applied to this case, that would require a working cash working capital of $321,000 and the petition for rehearing set forth a verbatim transcript of this witness' testimony before the State Commission and asked for further hearing before the I.C.C., which was denied.","start":980.577,"stop":1007.554,"duration":26.98},{"text":"The --","start":1007.554,"stop":1008.066,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the new evidence that you referred to?","start":1008.066,"stop":1011.121,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the new evidence that -- upon which we asked for reopening, that's right.","start":1011.121,"stop":1015.283,"duration":4.16},{"text":"And our amendment insofar as it relates to that charges, abuse of discretion in the denial of the hearing because that testimony would be directly contrary, not only to what was testified before the I.C.C., but also would invalidate the I.C.C.'s conclusion that $250,000 in cash working capital would be adequate.","start":1015.283,"stop":1037.626,"duration":22.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean this is new evidence that hadn't been before the Commission?","start":1037.626,"stop":1041.157,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1041.157,"stop":1041.933,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the provision of the statute, if any, which (Inaudible) the power of the District Court to hear new evidence?","start":1041.933,"stop":1049.019,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not new evidence which we wanted to present to the District Court.","start":1049.019,"stop":1052.826,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You wanted the case to go back to the Commission?","start":1052.826,"stop":1054.407,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"We're charging that the District Court on this phase of it should have held that the Interstate Commerce Commission should reopen the proceeding and take the evidence.","start":1054.407,"stop":1061.512,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On the basis of the new evidence facing for it.","start":1061.512,"stop":1064.545,"duration":3.03},{"text":"You wanted -- you want the District Court's dissent not to decide any of the issues presented back to the Commission?","start":1064.545,"stop":1070.129,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"This was on the basis of new evidence submitted to the Interstate Commerce Commission on the petition for rehearing which was denied.","start":1070.129,"stop":1075.456,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) that is -- the Commission denied that.","start":1075.456,"stop":1079,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1079,"stop":1080.106,"duration":1.11},{"text":"That's correct.","start":1080.106,"stop":1080.807,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A very good reason?","start":1080.807,"stop":1082.084,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1082.084,"stop":1082.712,"duration":0.63},{"text":"I just simply denied it in order --","start":1082.712,"stop":1084.652,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"After the case was closed before it.","start":1084.652,"stop":1086.803,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"It was -- while the time for petition for rehearing was still open.","start":1086.803,"stop":1090.595,"duration":3.79},{"text":"This testimony that I'm mentioning was given two weeks after the Interstate Commerce Commission handed down.","start":1090.595,"stop":1095.451,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) How long had the case been before the Commission (Inaudible) been before the Examiner?","start":1095.451,"stop":1102.874,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The case was heard by the Examiner in April of 1954.","start":1102.874,"stop":1107.446,"duration":4.57},{"text":"The Examiner rendered his proposed report recommending denial of the application in the fall of 1955 and -- I am sorry, in the fall of 1954.","start":1107.446,"stop":1118.044,"duration":10.6},{"text":"And thereafter, the entire Commission heard our argument and in July of 1955, issued its order granting the application.","start":1118.044,"stop":1125.581,"duration":7.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, was -- in your petition for reopening the case, did you lay the ground that this is a newly discovered evidence --","start":1125.581,"stop":1133.063,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we did.","start":1133.063,"stop":1133.29,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which is not capable of having been produced during all this time?","start":1133.29,"stop":1137.078,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we did and it --","start":1137.078,"stop":1138.313,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What makes -- why would this -- why was it not available before?","start":1138.313,"stop":1142.536,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it was a testimony given by the principal Greyhound witness given for the first time after the Interstate Commerce Commission decision come down but relating to the very issue of what's necessary working capital for this kind of an operation.","start":1142.536,"stop":1157.603,"duration":15.07}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, would have been useful to you in cross-examining him before the Commission if you -- if you had that -- that if he testified, you -- you have that (Inaudible) is that it?","start":1157.603,"stop":1168.325,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Not only that, Your Honor, but in the phase of that, since he was the principal Greyhound witness, the Interstate Commerce Commission, if they heard that testimony, could not possibly have concluded that $250,000 would be work-adequate capital.","start":1168.325,"stop":1181.157,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this later testimony of his was not capable of having been carried it out by you?","start":1181.157,"stop":1187.218,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1187.218,"stop":1187.882,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why not?","start":1187.882,"stop":1188.813,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it's -- it's something which they speak from their own knowledge.","start":1188.813,"stop":1192.491,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- this was expert evidence?","start":1192.491,"stop":1194.699,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"This is --","start":1194.699,"stop":1195.671,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Rather available figures.","start":1195.671,"stop":1197.006,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Well, I just want to know.","start":1197.006,"stop":1197.901,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1197.901,"stop":1198.148,"duration":0.25},{"text":"The -- the thing that was not available to us was Greyhound's own judgment as to what is necessary working capital.","start":1198.148,"stop":1206.551,"duration":8.4},{"text":"And this was the vice president of Greyhound testifying in one case that $150,000 is adequate, testifying in another case where it's to their advantage to build up the rate base that there should be included in the rate base an amount equal to one month's cash expenditures as necessary working capital.","start":1206.551,"stop":1225.787,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the time period was the same and the conditions were the same?","start":1225.787,"stop":1228.69,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- it's essentially the same operation, Your Honor.","start":1228.69,"stop":1232.025,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the same operation.","start":1232.025,"stop":1233.12,"duration":1.09},{"text":"They may well be in this case of fluctuating prices.","start":1233.12,"stop":1237.121,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that the question of what proportion of your expenses you need as cash working capital would be affected by time.","start":1237.121,"stop":1245.331,"duration":8.21},{"text":"It might be affected by whether they are the same operations or not, but I don't think --","start":1245.331,"stop":1248.93,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"These are ratios and not amount?","start":1248.93,"stop":1250.559,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1250.559,"stop":1251.3,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"When was the testimony given before the I.C.C.that $150,000 would be adequate?","start":1251.3,"stop":1256.715,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"In April of 1954.","start":1256.715,"stop":1259.047,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"When did he testify (Inaudible)","start":1259.047,"stop":1265.189,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it -- he testified before the State Commission in July of 1955 and his testimony was that cash working capital had to be in the amount of one-twelfth of the annual cash expenditures.","start":1265.189,"stop":1281.356,"duration":16.17},{"text":"And that formula, as applied to the showing made in this case before the Interstate Commerce Commission on the basis of the expenses shown to the Interstate Commerce Commission, would be $321,000 cash working capital.","start":1281.356,"stop":1294.757,"duration":13.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the Commission found what was -- that was adequate?","start":1294.757,"stop":1298.05,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"$250,000.","start":1298.05,"stop":1303.724,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and I gather that both proceedings are (Inaudible)","start":1303.724,"stop":1307.254,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"This very company and almost exactly the same operation.","start":1307.254,"stop":1311.917,"duration":4.66},{"text":"The State Utility Commission proceeding involved the rates for the Marin and Peninsula services.","start":1311.917,"stop":1317.814,"duration":5.9},{"text":"These proceeding involved those two plus the Contra Costa County, which is the smaller portion.","start":1317.814,"stop":1323.446,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, despite -- well, despite present cross-examined before your State Commission regarding his contradictory and so forth on your place, contradicted testimony before the Commission?","start":1323.446,"stop":1334.238,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"He was not -- no.","start":1334.238,"stop":1335.269,"duration":1.03},{"text":"He was cross-examined as to whether he was sure that you needed this much working capital and he became quite emphatic in saying that you have to have this much.","start":1335.269,"stop":1343.137,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did your Commission have the -- his testimony before the Interstate Commerce Commission?","start":1343.137,"stop":1348.016,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- no, the Commission didn't have it.","start":1348.016,"stop":1352.57,"duration":4.55},{"text":"This cross-examination, Your Honor, was by myself as counsel for these same people who were appellants here.","start":1352.57,"stop":1359.28,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then that would be more confounded now.","start":1359.28,"stop":1362.679,"duration":3.4},{"text":"You were before the Commission, the Interstate Commerce Commission?","start":1362.679,"stop":1365.017,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1365.017,"stop":1365.64,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You heard his testimony?","start":1365.64,"stop":1366.839,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1366.839,"stop":1367.435,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You knew him?","start":1367.435,"stop":1368.39,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1368.39,"stop":1369.051,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you cross-examine him before your State Commission regarding his contradiction?","start":1369.051,"stop":1374.713,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":1374.713,"stop":1376.456,"duration":1.74},{"text":"I --","start":1376.456,"stop":1376.562,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, then, why shouldn't -- why should the I.C.C. a part of the contradiction?","start":1376.562,"stop":1380.382,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's obviously contradictory, Your Honor.","start":1380.382,"stop":1381.993,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- it was so obvious that you didn't make the point.","start":1381.993,"stop":1386.103,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the point that was involved there was a different issue from what's involved here.","start":1386.103,"stop":1390.397,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I -- I should think the reliability of a witness is an issue -- is -- is issue that goes to the value of the testimony.","start":1390.397,"stop":1396.16,"duration":5.76}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I might say that there -- insofar as reliability of the witness is concern, there was considerable cross-examination on other points in which contradictions had been developed.","start":1396.16,"stop":1405.973,"duration":9.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a fact that you did not make use of his prior different testimony on the same portion, but you're not willing to say important, is that right?","start":1405.973,"stop":1414.608,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Not before the State Commission.","start":1414.608,"stop":1415.826,"duration":1.22},{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1415.826,"stop":1416.718,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But you did rather use it before the I.C.C., next to the rehearing where it was relevant.","start":1416.718,"stop":1422.6,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and it's set forth verbatim in the petition for rehearing filed before the Interstate Commerce Commission and it's in the record.","start":1422.6,"stop":1428.384,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you saying it wasn't relevant for you to cross-examine him on his inconsistency?","start":1428.384,"stop":1433.527,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Before the State Commission, it would have been relevant.","start":1433.527,"stop":1435.438,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Oh, I don't say it's not relevant.","start":1435.438,"stop":1437.675,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You didn't deem it's relevant.","start":1437.675,"stop":1439.117,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"There are a lot of things which are relevant in --","start":1439.117,"stop":1440.68,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1440.68,"stop":1440.754,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- cross-examination which the Examiner --","start":1440.754,"stop":1443.058,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1443.058,"stop":1443.122,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I deem it relevant, but I didn't deem it within the scope of -- of my judgment as to why I should cross-examine him in the context of everything else in which I cross-examine.","start":1443.122,"stop":1451.673,"duration":8.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If he happened to decide whether the Commission was within its discretionary power in not opening the case, is that right?","start":1451.673,"stop":1458.081,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1458.081,"stop":1458.748,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1458.748,"stop":1459.143,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":1459.143,"stop":1459.704,"duration":0.56},{"text":"No -- no, I don't.","start":1459.704,"stop":1460.277,"duration":0.57},{"text":"That's -- the question here is whether the lower court should have permitted us to make the amendment to raise this question.","start":1460.277,"stop":1467.308,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then, the question before it was, whether the Commission abused its discretion and not reopen the case --","start":1467.308,"stop":1473.033,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1473.033,"stop":1473.549,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and that's the question here whether the District Court allowably said that that wasn't exercise, not an abuse of discretion, is that right?","start":1473.549,"stop":1481.393,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"On that branch of it, yes.","start":1481.393,"stop":1482.65,"duration":1.26},{"text":"And, of course, our men would also challenge the public interest findings --","start":1482.65,"stop":1486.317,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's (Inaudible)","start":1486.317,"stop":1487.125,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1487.125,"stop":1487.775,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's certainly as though it states here of a question whether the State Commission (Inaudible)","start":1487.775,"stop":1495.265,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1495.265,"stop":1496.183,"duration":0.92},{"text":"No, that is not involved.","start":1496.183,"stop":1498.686,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that will not -- the outcome here will not determine (Inaudible)","start":1498.686,"stop":1503.844,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in a legal sense.","start":1503.844,"stop":1504.771,"duration":0.93},{"text":"In a realistic sense, the -- there's a great bearing on rates, of course --","start":1504.771,"stop":1508.401,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I understand there --","start":1508.401,"stop":1509.489,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because in -- in a realistic sense, if the separation goes through, then in an application for rates involving this local service, the only carrier before the State Commission will be the Golden Gate subsidiary.","start":1509.489,"stop":1524.545,"duration":15.06},{"text":"And this will circumvent what the State Commission has been applying as a policy of considering Greyhound's windfall in the rest of the State in deciding what the rates for this service should be.","start":1524.545,"stop":1539.105,"duration":14.56},{"text":"Now, I feel -- if the Court please, that this question of whether we should have been permitted to make this amendment in the lower court is effectively controlled by what this Court did just a month ago in Spevack versus Strauss, 355 U.S.601, where in granting certiorari, it directed that the matter be remanded to the Court of Appeals with directions to allow an amendment to the complaint which had been presented there for the first time in the Court of Appeals.","start":1539.105,"stop":1580.456,"duration":41.35},{"text":"This reflects the liberal rules of pleading set forth in 15 (a) of the Civil Rules.","start":1580.456,"stop":1587.009,"duration":6.55},{"text":"And certainly, if it was an abuse of discretion for the Court of Appeals to deny an amendment presented for the first time in that Court, then all the more, in our case, where we presented the amendment at the outset of arguments on motions for summary judgment in the District Court, the amendment should have been allowed.","start":1587.009,"stop":1609.035,"duration":22.03},{"text":"And I might say that the Court took 14 months to deny our motion to amend.","start":1609.035,"stop":1618.208,"duration":9.17},{"text":"Our motion to amend was made in February of 1956.","start":1618.208,"stop":1622.196,"duration":3.99},{"text":"It was set down for oral argument in April of 1956 and it was not denied by the District Court until April of 1957, a full 14 months after we filed the motion so that it can -- the action of the lower court can hardly be explained or defended on the ground that it would have unfairly delayed disposition of the case.","start":1622.196,"stop":1651.021,"duration":28.83},{"text":"The lower court did not contend that the amendment was insubstantial.","start":1651.021,"stop":1655.739,"duration":4.72},{"text":"On the contrary, it said only that in the absence of a showing of mistake, inadvertence, neglect or changed conditions, the amendment should not be allowed.","start":1655.739,"stop":1667.001,"duration":11.26},{"text":"These are the criteria which govern the granting of relief from a default judgment and not the criteria which govern the granting of amendments to pleadings.","start":1667.001,"stop":1679.042,"duration":12.04},{"text":"I pass now to the question of the applicability of Section 5 to split-ups.","start":1679.042,"stop":1686.78,"duration":7.74},{"text":"The statutory language itself quite clearly shows that split-ups are not contemplated by Section 5.","start":1686.78,"stop":1696.764,"duration":9.98},{"text":"It sets forth five classes of transactions, and if my telescope the language but read what I read verbatim, the five classes are as follows, and these are set forth on pages 22 and 23 of our main brief, “For two or more carriers to consolidate or merge their properties or franchises into one corporation.","start":1696.764,"stop":1723.202,"duration":26.44},{"text":"Secondly, for any carrier to purchase lease or contract to operate the properties of another.","start":1723.202,"stop":1731.675,"duration":8.47},{"text":"Third, for any carrier to acquire control of another.","start":1731.675,"stop":1737.749,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Fourth, for a person which is not a carrier to acquire control of two or more carriers.","start":1737.749,"stop":1745.61,"duration":7.86},{"text":"And fifth, for a person which is not a carrier and which has control of one or more carriers to acquire control of another carrier.”","start":1745.61,"stop":1757.053,"duration":11.44},{"text":"In every instance, we start out with two or more carriers to come within these provisions.","start":1757.053,"stop":1765.08,"duration":8.03},{"text":"Now, the Commission in the lower court applied the provision -- the third provision, which I read which is, “For any carrier to acquire control of another”.","start":1765.08,"stop":1779.704,"duration":14.62},{"text":"And the reasoning of the Commission in the lower court was that on the consummation of this transaction, Golden Gate, which is presently not a carrier, will become a carrier once it gets into the operation of the -- of the service which is proposed to be transferred.","start":1779.704,"stop":1800.958,"duration":21.25},{"text":"It will become a carrier and at that time, it will be controlled by its parent, Greyhound, which is a carrier and therefore, we have claimed by operation bootstrap into a situation of one carrier acquiring control of another carrier.","start":1800.958,"stop":1821.803,"duration":20.85},{"text":"Not only does this do violence to the language of Section 5, but it is completely inconsistent with the purposes of Section 5 as clearly shown by the legislative history, as this Court has frequently itself set forth in its opinions.","start":1821.803,"stop":1840.264,"duration":18.46},{"text":"This provision, Section 5, as written into the 1940 Transportation Act had, as its purpose, the provision of means of relief for a very sick transportation industry.","start":1840.264,"stop":1856.581,"duration":16.32},{"text":"In the 1920 Act, which was passed when the Government was turning the operation of the railroad back to the companies, Congress had decided upon the approach of imposing on the Interstate Commerce Commission the obligation to formulate plans of consolidation of railroads into a relatively few systems.","start":1856.581,"stop":1880.033,"duration":23.45},{"text":"And once the Commission formulated and announced a consolidation plan, carriers could then initiate mergers and consolidations but that approach never worked because the Commission never got around to formulating a plan of consolidation.","start":1880.033,"stop":1898.937,"duration":18.9},{"text":"So finally, after lengthy studies by presidential committees and congressional committees, in the 1940 Act, this was all changed.","start":1898.937,"stop":1912.482,"duration":13.55},{"text":"The obligation on the Commission to formulate plans was removed and carriers were given the authority to initiate voluntarily, merger and consolidation plans subject to the requirement that they must be approved by the Commission as consistent with the public interest.","start":1912.482,"stop":1932.697,"duration":20.21},{"text":"The Committee Report show that Congress was dealing with an industry which was described as being one-third in bankruptcy and the other third on the verge, and the need for providing effective and practical means of consolidating weak carriers was urgent.","start":1932.697,"stop":1954.166,"duration":21.47},{"text":"Obviously, in the case particularly of large carriers, mergers and consolidations could not effectively be carried out if the approval were required of every other regulatory agency which might have jurisdiction over any portion of the transaction.","start":1954.166,"stop":1974.237,"duration":20.07},{"text":"And for that reason, Congress provided that once approved by the Commission, this merger and consolidation plans could be carried out regardless of the antitrust laws and without invoking the approval of any federal agency or of any state agency.","start":1974.237,"stop":1994.496,"duration":20.26}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1994.496,"stop":2000.469,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":2000.469,"stop":2002.302,"duration":1.83},{"text":"It was to -- in --","start":2002.302,"stop":2003.31,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"By split-up -- the split-up based in the Committee Reports?","start":2003.31,"stop":2006.56,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Never.","start":2006.56,"stop":2007.28,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Every term in this Committee Reports is in the line of merger, consolidation, cooling, unification, combination, acquiring common control, all the language and all of the discussion is in terms of enabling weak carriers to combine.","start":2007.28,"stop":2025.11,"duration":17.83},{"text":"What Greyhound proposes to do here is to cut off the weak member of its single corporate body and send it out to flounder for itself and very proudly to die in the bankruptcy courts, and to do this under the -- the purported authority of a statute which was designed to encourage just the opposite form --","start":2025.11,"stop":2051.5,"duration":26.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the Commission therefore applied Section 5 to split-up?","start":2051.5,"stop":2056.976,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 5 has been applied to split-ups by the Commission, so far as I know from my own research and briefs of the appellees in five cases.","start":2056.976,"stop":2067.143,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) what's the other?","start":2067.143,"stop":2068.388,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The earliest case is 1940.","start":2068.388,"stop":2071.094,"duration":2.71},{"text":"The second case is 1940 --","start":2071.094,"stop":2072.447,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 5 is 1920, came in 1920.","start":2072.447,"stop":2075.034,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- in its present form, it came in 1940.","start":2075.034,"stop":2079.467,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know but it's -- it came in originally and it might be in 1920.","start":2079.467,"stop":2084.279,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, yes.","start":2084.279,"stop":2085.827,"duration":1.55},{"text":"Now, those two cases in 1940 and 1941 are the only Commission cases decided prior to the time when we contested this construction before the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":2085.827,"stop":2099.566,"duration":13.74},{"text":"So, the administrative history up to the point where we challenged it in our case consists of these two cases in 1940 and 1941.","start":2099.566,"stop":2108.582,"duration":9.02},{"text":"Neither of those two cases were they contested proceeding, there was nobody before the Commission objecting to what was being done.","start":2108.582,"stop":2115.766,"duration":7.18},{"text":"And as our supplemental brief shows in the first of these, the 1940 case, Columbia Terminals, the carriers themselves didn't rely upon the exclusive authority of the Commission but they went to the State Commission and got approval from the State Commission for the transfer of the intrastate right involved.","start":2115.766,"stop":2134.09,"duration":18.32},{"text":"That's the total administrative interpretation prior to the commencement of our case.","start":2134.09,"stop":2139.374,"duration":5.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Hasn't there been any provision decision at all (Inaudible)","start":2139.374,"stop":2142.379,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the three decisions since are in 1954, 1956 and 1957.","start":2142.379,"stop":2148.826,"duration":6.45},{"text":"They likewise involved proceedings in which there was nobody protesting what was being done.","start":2148.826,"stop":2154.926,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How they get into court?","start":2154.926,"stop":2156.208,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"They didn't get into court.","start":2156.208,"stop":2157.014,"duration":0.81},{"text":"These are all Commission decision.","start":2157.014,"stop":2158.101,"duration":1.09},{"text":"There are no court decisions.","start":2158.101,"stop":2160.37,"duration":2.27},{"text":"There's -- there's never been anybody in these Commission proceedings who showed an interest in the matter and who therefore would have been in the position to go into court on this.","start":2160.37,"stop":2169.177,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Our decisions turned over (Inaudible)","start":2169.177,"stop":2173.255,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Every decision of this Court and of any other court has been in the field of mergers.","start":2173.255,"stop":2179.093,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2179.093,"stop":2183.627,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we don't reach the question which divided the Court there because in that case, you had several existing carriers already under a common control with a proposal to -- to strengthen or increase the control by a -- a merger of some of the controlled entities into the other.","start":2183.627,"stop":2202.558,"duration":18.93},{"text":"And the question there which divided the Court would whether that transaction constituted an acquisition of control or whether the control had already been acquired by previous transactions.So, we don't reach that question here at all.","start":2202.558,"stop":2219.475,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On this question, on this issue, what was the difference between the Act of 1920 about which Justice Brennan asked you and the Transportation Act of 1940?","start":2219.475,"stop":2228.122,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar as split-ups are concerned?","start":2228.122,"stop":2229.935,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, in both.","start":2229.935,"stop":2231.504,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"How?","start":2231.504,"stop":2232.208,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In regard to the actual content of what is now Section 5.","start":2232.208,"stop":2236.06,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The 19 --","start":2236.06,"stop":2236.701,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) as you said it was a supplanting of the provisions.","start":2236.701,"stop":2239.635,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2239.635,"stop":2239.855,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In 19 -- in 1920 Act, the Transportation Act of 1920, this both case, it both authorized -- made provision for authorization, consolidation and mergers and also directed the Commission to make a comprehensive plan to unify the railroad system.","start":2239.855,"stop":2255.4,"duration":15.55}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but --","start":2255.4,"stop":2255.55,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but he sure is paying and therefore, that was cut out in the 1940 amendment.","start":2255.55,"stop":2260.475,"duration":4.92},{"text":"What I want to know is, what were the changes, the subsequent changes between the authorizations of the 1920 and 1940 Acts in relating to the same subject?","start":2260.475,"stop":2269.901,"duration":9.43}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The big change, Your Honor, was that under the 1920 Act, the carriers could not initiate a merger or consolidation unless the Commission had first announced a consolidation plan.","start":2269.901,"stop":2284.347,"duration":14.45},{"text":"And then, consistently with the announced consolidation plan, carriers could propose mergers consistent with them.","start":2284.347,"stop":2291.123,"duration":6.78},{"text":"The 1940 Act --","start":2291.123,"stop":2292.388,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Cut -- cut the first cutout.","start":2292.388,"stop":2293.944,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2293.944,"stop":2294.072,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2294.072,"stop":2297.416,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the (Inaudible)","start":2297.416,"stop":2303.783,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"In the --","start":2303.783,"stop":2304.365,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2304.365,"stop":2307.746,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"When the Motor Carrier Act was first enacted in 1935, it provided for mergers and consolidations with the approval of the Interstate Commerce Commission in pretty much the same language which is contained in the 1940 amendment to Section 5 and at that time the motor carrier provisions were repealed from -- from part two of the Motor Carrier Act and motor carriers were brought under Section 5 along with water carriers and the railroads.","start":2307.746,"stop":2340.324,"duration":32.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, a railroad, these are motor carriers, a railroad couldn't divest itself as part of its system, could it, without permission?","start":2340.324,"stop":2348.763,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2348.763,"stop":2350.129,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What provision was there to allow divestiture, a part of a railroad system by transferring it to some other railroads?","start":2350.129,"stop":2359.111,"duration":8.98}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the divestment by transfer would have had to have been by approval of the Commission in terms of a purchase of one portion of the carrier's property by another carrier.","start":2359.111,"stop":2370.627,"duration":11.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"To that extent, there was a split off provided for or authorized by the Act.","start":2370.627,"stop":2375.972,"duration":5.35},{"text":"If you're going to use word like “split off,” there was a split off, wasn't it?","start":2375.972,"stop":2379.214,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- this --","start":2379.214,"stop":2379.962,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Whenever there was a divestment of a system of railroads --","start":2379.962,"stop":2383.397,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- as long as --","start":2383.397,"stop":2383.723,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) its activities, there's a split off?","start":2383.723,"stop":2386.399,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- in that sense, yes.","start":2386.399,"stop":2387.749,"duration":1.35},{"text":"As long as it goes from one carrier to another carrier, it's within Section 5 but the -- the split-up and I use “split-up” rather than “split off” to distinguish that situation, the split-up here does not involve a transfer to some other existing carrier but rather the subdivision of a single carrier into two units.","start":2387.749,"stop":2412.195,"duration":24.45},{"text":"The vice of this situation --","start":2412.195,"stop":2414.992,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"My suggest to it -- I suppose you would say in that case there is a -- a merger of the really acquiring road into divesting road.","start":2414.992,"stop":2423.914,"duration":8.92},{"text":"That's -- that's the difference, isn't it?","start":2423.914,"stop":2425.913,"duration":2},{"text":"But here, there's -- there's an internal separation.","start":2425.913,"stop":2429.829,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2429.829,"stop":2430.494,"duration":0.66},{"text":"This -- this is like an -- an amoeba --","start":2430.494,"stop":2433.335,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2433.335,"stop":2433.515,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- subdividing itself.","start":2433.515,"stop":2434.644,"duration":1.13},{"text":"Only the amoeba has the protoplasmic quality to create a completely new and independent unit out of its subdivision whereas --","start":2434.644,"stop":2442.707,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Here -- here, you have to get somebody's permission?","start":2442.707,"stop":2445.816,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and here in addition, the segment being cut-off realistically is not going to be able to grow into successful and healthy manhood, but rather, it's being cut-off in -- in such a way that the operation itself is going to be a weak floundering and probably a dying operation.","start":2445.816,"stop":2466.589,"duration":20.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the conclusion of your contention that if a railroad or motor enterprise would like to cut-off a non-paid aspect, it cannot so rid itself of a vesting asset unless it is able to transfer to an existing parent.","start":2466.589,"stop":2488.742,"duration":22.15},{"text":"Is that your -- that's what it get down to business.","start":2488.742,"stop":2490.63,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, with this qualification.","start":2490.63,"stop":2492.75,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Not state approval?","start":2492.75,"stop":2493.733,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That if it gets state approval, it may have been.","start":2493.733,"stop":2495.391,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":2495.391,"stop":2495.902,"duration":0.51},{"text":"It's about the Commission people.","start":2495.902,"stop":2497.274,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2497.274,"stop":2497.899,"duration":0.63},{"text":"It would have to get the approval whatever Commission had jurisdiction over that particular branch or segment.","start":2497.899,"stop":2502.849,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Court has rendered some decisions that I respect, but I don't agree with it at the time which made also to (Inaudible) on requirement of state approval.","start":2502.849,"stop":2512.789,"duration":9.94},{"text":"I'm thinking of Schwabacher case (Inaudible)","start":2512.789,"stop":2515.124,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2515.124,"stop":2515.39,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not saying that -- that's Schwabacher but I'm -- I'm indicating the attitude of this Court for all those problems, the state-interstate relation.","start":2515.39,"stop":2522.922,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the -- the case which comes closest to applying the philosophy which we think applies here is the decision of this Court last January in the Chicago Commuter case, the Milwaukee Road case in which the Interstate Commerce Commission made an order increasing the intrastate commuter rates on the ground that they constituted -- the existing rates constitute a burden on interstate commerce and this Court held in setting that aside that the finding of that type could not be supported unless the entire intrastate rate structure --","start":2522.922,"stop":2557.978,"duration":35.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If that was closer --","start":2557.978,"stop":2558.342,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"-- was inevitable.","start":2558.342,"stop":2559.093,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's pretty far away so far as I'm concern.","start":2559.093,"stop":2560.59,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the factually, of course, is -- is different but the philosophy which the Court express about the need for a scrupulous regard for the State -- interest of the State under the federal system which we have, the philosophy expressed in that opinion applies here in the sense that the Court should not oust the jurisdiction of state agencies under Section 5, unless the transaction is of the type which Section 5 was designed to meet.","start":2560.59,"stop":2594.566,"duration":33.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we've got -- those are really different problems.","start":2594.566,"stop":2597.218,"duration":2.65},{"text":"That's the question on the floor when you display a conceded state rate.","start":2597.218,"stop":2604.052,"duration":6.83},{"text":"All right.","start":2604.052,"stop":2604.414,"duration":0.36},{"text":"All I'm saying is, if you say that's the closest, then we've got to make new law here.","start":2604.414,"stop":2608.102,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Spurgeon Avakian","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I say it's close in -- in the philosophy expressed, not in the issue presented, Your Honor.","start":2608.102,"stop":2618.274,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ginnane.","start":2618.274,"stop":2625.336,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2625.336,"stop":2629.423,"duration":4.09},{"text":"I would like to first to discuss the facts relating to the posture of this case, what has been properly before the District Court and what we believe is properly before this Court.","start":2629.423,"stop":2642.37,"duration":12.95},{"text":"Now, the court proceeding began on October 1955 and these appellants filed their complaint and it's in the record of pages 1 to 7.","start":2642.37,"stop":2651.912,"duration":9.54},{"text":"And on that complaint, they attacked the Commission's orders solely on a single ground that transactions of this type, split-up as they call it, are not subject to the Commission's jurisdiction under Section 5.","start":2651.912,"stop":2666.374,"duration":14.46},{"text":"Nothing was said in there about the rate, policies to California Commission, nothing about the sufficiency of the Commission's findings, their support on the evidence or anything else.","start":2666.374,"stop":2676.21,"duration":9.84},{"text":"Simply, the question of whether this type of transaction is covered by Section 5.","start":2676.21,"stop":2683.584,"duration":7.37},{"text":"As the appellants have stated, thereafter both the appellants and the defendants, United States and Interstate Commerce Commission filed motions for judgment in the pleadings.","start":2683.584,"stop":2693.545,"duration":9.96},{"text":"It was perfectly clear what everybody was doing.","start":2693.545,"stop":2697.424,"duration":3.88},{"text":"The appellants stated in their own motion that they so moved for the reason that the pleadings of the various parties showed that there is no question of fact involved in the case and that the sole question recited is one of law.","start":2697.424,"stop":2711.964,"duration":14.54},{"text":"Plaintiffs did not file to the District Court the record of the evidence received before the Commission.","start":2711.964,"stop":2717.989,"duration":6.03},{"text":"That evidence is not before this Court.","start":2717.989,"stop":2722.124,"duration":4.13},{"text":"Then, the case went to argument before the three judges.","start":2722.124,"stop":2726.371,"duration":4.25},{"text":"And it was only in the course of the oral argument before three federal judges.","start":2726.371,"stop":2731.673,"duration":5.3},{"text":"Now, for the first time, we'd heard about this proposal to amend the complaint in the course of the argument.","start":2731.673,"stop":2740.611,"duration":8.94},{"text":"The appellant's counsel stated that he intended, \"To,\" and I quote, \"To ask leave of the Court in the event the determination of the Court should be against us on the legal question raised to give us permission to amend the complaint, to set forth as an additional ground the challenge of the finding of the Commission that the order in question is consistent with the public interest\".","start":2740.611,"stop":2762.992,"duration":22.38},{"text":"And not even at that point, if may I point out, not even at that point did he say anything about challenging the Commission's action in refusing to reopen the case for rehearing and reconsideration.","start":2762.992,"stop":2776.6,"duration":13.61},{"text":"And it was not until February 28, five days after the oral argument before the three-judge court that these appellants filed their motion for leave to amend their complaint.","start":2776.6,"stop":2790.739,"duration":14.14},{"text":"The District Court heard argument on this motion.","start":2790.739,"stop":2794.453,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Then on April 12, 1957, the three-judge court handed down its decision.","start":2794.453,"stop":2799.841,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean there's a separate argument on this after the main argument?","start":2799.841,"stop":2803.091,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in April 1956.","start":2803.091,"stop":2806.587,"duration":3.5},{"text":"The three-judge court called us out to -- to argue on whether the motion to amend should be granted.","start":2806.587,"stop":2812.183,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any response from the -- from the Court at the time they first mentioned that they wanted to amend the complaint?","start":2812.183,"stop":2820.182,"duration":8},{"text":"Did the -- did the Court intimate whether it would entertain the motion of that kind or not?","start":2820.182,"stop":2828.665,"duration":8.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want to make an erroneous statement here, but I don't think the Court gave very much of a response.","start":2828.665,"stop":2836.342,"duration":7.68},{"text":"I would like to check that in the --","start":2836.342,"stop":2837.74,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2837.74,"stop":2838.54,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"If I'm in error, I would like to saw it on.","start":2838.54,"stop":2840.147,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2840.147,"stop":2842.706,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we contend that the District Court did not err in denying this motion.","start":2842.706,"stop":2848.671,"duration":5.96},{"text":"Because this motion, for the first time, asked leave to amend the complaint in two major respects, first, to allege that the Commission's order was not supported by substantial evidence, and second, that the Commission's action in -- in denying the -- the appellant's petition for reconsideration involved an abuse of discretion by the Commission.","start":2848.671,"stop":2870.197,"duration":21.53},{"text":"That -- it's admitted, has been from the beginning, that this was not due to any inadvertence or mistake on the part of the appellants.","start":2870.197,"stop":2878.577,"duration":8.38},{"text":"It was a deliberate tactical choice.","start":2878.577,"stop":2880.94,"duration":2.36},{"text":"They, themselves, state it with candor.","start":2880.94,"stop":2883.718,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The question of insufficiency of evidence isn't -- isn't now being urged.It's not here, is it?","start":2883.718,"stop":2891.456,"duration":7.74},{"text":"But there is no basis in evidence.","start":2891.456,"stop":2892.969,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"You've heard quite a bit of argument on that the --","start":2892.969,"stop":2895.218,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm -- in the questions -- that is not as ever a specific issue here, is it?","start":2895.218,"stop":2901.51,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it is.","start":2901.51,"stop":2903.318,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm not (Inaudible) in my question.","start":2903.318,"stop":2908.618,"duration":5.3},{"text":"I look at the (Voice Overlap) --","start":2908.618,"stop":2908.923,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"But nor I in my reply brief.","start":2908.923,"stop":2911.09,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and that is not presented as it's -- you said there are two questions were raised --","start":2911.09,"stop":2914.465,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2914.465,"stop":2914.611,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- namely, there's no basis in evidence of what the Commission did.","start":2914.611,"stop":2919.047,"duration":4.44},{"text":"And two, the case should be sent back to the Commission for further hearing.","start":2919.047,"stop":2922.445,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2922.445,"stop":2923.18,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the matter is being urged that (Inaudible) is being urged that the formal, the insufficiency of this none adequacy of the evidence is not here (Inaudible)","start":2923.18,"stop":2933.713,"duration":10.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, sir.","start":2933.713,"stop":2934.875,"duration":1.16},{"text":"But I make this very clear that the original complaint filed in the District Court made no attack on the Commission's action in refusing to reopen the proceeding.","start":2934.875,"stop":2946.812,"duration":11.94},{"text":"That issue too, like the sufficiency of the evidence, was raised only in this motion to amend --","start":2946.812,"stop":2951.597,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":2951.597,"stop":2952.38,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"-- filed after the argument before the three-judge court.","start":2952.38,"stop":2956.386,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the sufficiency of the evidence is based on his ideas, as I understood it, maybe I'm wrong, because the Court declined to permit the amendment.","start":2956.386,"stop":2963.563,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, sir.","start":2963.563,"stop":2964.28,"duration":0.72},{"text":"Correct, sir.","start":2964.28,"stop":2966.793,"duration":2.51},{"text":"Now, the appellants based their argument on Rule 15 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, which provides that after issue has been joined, a party may amend this proceeding only by leave of court or by written consent of the adverse party and leave shall be grant -- given freely when justice so requires.","start":2966.793,"stop":2985.778,"duration":18.98},{"text":"But we submit that Rule 15 is directed largely, primarily at the amendment of pleadings in connection with judicial trials.","start":2985.778,"stop":2995.82,"duration":10.04},{"text":"Every one of the -- of the cases, cited by the appellants on this point, relates the amendment of pleadings in cases tried by the courts.","start":2995.82,"stop":3006.023,"duration":10.2},{"text":"We are concerned, as we see it, in this situation with an amendment or pleadings in the usual sense at all, because what the appellants are trying to do here is not just a little old amendment of a pleading, It amounts to a deliberate attempt.","start":3006.023,"stop":3022.09,"duration":16.07},{"text":"It's almost unique to subject administrative orders to piecemeal successive review or rolling review.","start":3022.09,"stop":3031.342,"duration":9.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't quite understand that.","start":3031.342,"stop":3034.098,"duration":2.76},{"text":"They filed a complaint here.","start":3034.098,"stop":3035.294,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"They filed a complaint.","start":3035.294,"stop":3036.679,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They asked to amend the complaint.","start":3036.679,"stop":3038.482,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"They filed a complaint.","start":3038.482,"stop":3039.682,"duration":1.2},{"text":"Would have -- we -- we have oral argument before three federal judges at the briefs.","start":3039.682,"stop":3042.809,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand -- do I understand you to say that it shouldn't be governed by that ruling so far as the pleading is freely amended?","start":3042.809,"stop":3053.446,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3053.446,"stop":3054.417,"duration":0.97},{"text":"That -- that's --","start":3054.417,"stop":3055.231,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it should be carved out as an exemption in connection with complaints challenging the I.C.C. (Inaudible)","start":3055.231,"stop":3060.758,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, because it's just a historical accident, Your Honor, that the Rules of Civil Procedure have any application here, if the historical accident that I.C.C. orders are not reviewable in the Circuit Courts of Appeal.","start":3060.758,"stop":3075.713,"duration":14.96},{"text":"If our orders were reviewable on the Courts of Appeals, say like the -- the orders of the Communications Commission, S.C.C. and the Labor Board, no one would seriously contend that Rule 15 could be applied to -- to permit such successive piecemeal review of administrative orders.","start":3075.713,"stop":3092.084,"duration":16.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How would that apply?","start":3092.084,"stop":3093.232,"duration":1.15},{"text":"I don't understand.","start":3093.232,"stop":3094.041,"duration":0.81},{"text":"I'm asking questions because I always thought that out of all the rules, probably that's one of the best rules, (Inaudible) allowing people where justice is required to amend their complaint at anytime before the Court (Inaudible) if justice is required and you -- and you (Inaudible) so as not to apply (Inaudible)","start":3094.041,"stop":3121.213,"duration":27.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"We have -- know of no case prior to this in which that has been urged as authority for permitting or encouraging successive piecemeal reviews of an administrative order.","start":3121.213,"stop":3133.648,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But aside from that, has -- has there ever been a case before where the questioning is argued or decided or argued if that rule would not apply to the pleading of this type?","start":3133.648,"stop":3145.35,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there has been no such case.We know of no previous attempt that so apply.","start":3145.35,"stop":3148.832,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there'd been many amendments, hasn't it?","start":3148.832,"stop":3152.791,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a -- talking about the -- sticking to -- sticking to the Commission's practice --","start":3152.791,"stop":3157.164,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) when they filed their complaint, there'd been many amendments, as I recall it, before the case is on.","start":3157.164,"stop":3163.645,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"It's --","start":3163.645,"stop":3163.845,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And I just think it might --","start":3163.845,"stop":3165.15,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"There --","start":3165.15,"stop":3165.259,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) but I don't understand why --","start":3165.259,"stop":3166.507,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"There have been a number.","start":3166.507,"stop":3167.012,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) a reason would require that this type of -- that we read it out is a (Inaudible)","start":3167.012,"stop":3173.617,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"Robert W. Ginnane","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there had been a number of cases in which shortly after a complaint has been filed in a three-judge court.","start":3173.617,"stop":3180.659,"duration":7.04},{"text":"Parties have offered an amendment.","start":3180.659,"stop":3183.986,"duration":3.33},{"text":"Neither the Government or intervening defendants have ever made any point of that where it's been done while in advance at hearing.","start":3183.986,"stop":3190.129,"duration":6.14},{"text":"At the most, we have asked for a postponement of hearing, a postponement of briefing dates in order to adjust to -- to the amendments to the complaint.","start":3190.129,"stop":3201.556,"duration":11.43},{"text":"But this chronology, this is unique in our practice, and so far as I know, in -- in the history of federal judicial review proceedings.","start":3201.556,"stop":3211.143,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3211.143,"stop":3214.921,"duration":3.78}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr 9, 1958","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"415","citation":"356 US 412 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/356/412","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 19, 1958"}